"""
Flow translations for Joshua — accurate, literal English renderings.
Every verse of all 24 chapters. Formal equivalence style.
YHWH = the LORD. Original translation from the Hebrew Masoretic Text.
Study notes included for key theological moments and Christ typology.
"""

FLOW_JOSHUA = {
    1: {  # Chapter 1
        1: 'Now it came about after the death of Moses the servant of the LORD, that the LORD spoke to Joshua the son of Nun, Moses\' assistant, saying,',
        2: '"Moses My servant is dead. Now therefore arise, cross over this Jordan, you and all this people, to the land which I am giving to them, to the sons of Israel.',
        3: 'Every place on which the sole of your foot treads, I have given it to you, just as I spoke to Moses.',
        4: 'From the wilderness and this Lebanon, even as far as the great river, the river Euphrates, all the land of the Hittites, and as far as the Great Sea toward the setting of the sun, shall be your territory.',
        5: 'No man shall be able to stand before you all the days of your life. Just as I was with Moses, so I will be with you; I will not fail you or forsake you.',
        6: 'Be strong and courageous, for you shall give this people possession of the land which I swore to their fathers to give them.',
        7: 'Only be strong and very courageous; be careful to do according to all the law which Moses My servant commanded you. Do not turn from it to the right or to the left, so that you may have success wherever you go.',
        8: 'This book of the law shall not depart from your mouth, but you shall meditate on it day and night, so that you may be careful to do according to all that is written in it; for then you will make your way prosperous, and then you will have good success.',
        9: 'Have I not commanded you? Be strong and courageous! Do not tremble or be dismayed, for the LORD your God is with you wherever you go."',
        10: 'Then Joshua commanded the officers of the people, saying,',
        11: '"Pass through the midst of the camp and command the people, saying, \'Prepare provisions for yourselves, for within three days you are to cross over this Jordan, to go in to take possession of the land which the LORD your God is giving you to possess.\'"',
        12: 'And to the Reubenites and to the Gadites and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, Joshua said,',
        13: '"Remember the word which Moses the servant of the LORD commanded you, saying, \'The LORD your God is giving you rest and is giving you this land.\'',
        14: 'Your wives, your little ones, and your livestock shall remain in the land which Moses gave you beyond the Jordan, but you shall cross over before your brothers in battle array, all your valiant warriors, and shall help them,',
        15: 'until the LORD gives your brothers rest, as He gives you, and they also take possession of the land which the LORD your God is giving them. Then you shall return to your own land and take possession of it, the land which Moses the servant of the LORD gave you beyond the Jordan toward the sunrise."',
        16: 'And they answered Joshua, saying, "All that you have commanded us we will do, and wherever you send us we will go.',
        17: 'Just as we obeyed Moses in all things, so we will obey you; only may the LORD your God be with you as He was with Moses.',
        18: 'Anyone who rebels against your command and does not obey your words in all that you command him shall be put to death. Only be strong and courageous."',
    },
    2: {  # Chapter 2
        1: 'Then Joshua the son of Nun sent two men as spies secretly from Shittim, saying, "Go, view the land, especially Jericho." So they went and came into the house of a woman, a prostitute whose name was Rahab, and lodged there.',
        2: 'And it was told to the king of Jericho, saying, "Behold, men from the sons of Israel have come here tonight to search out the land."',
        3: 'And the king of Jericho sent word to Rahab, saying, "Bring out the men who have come to you, who have entered your house, for they have come to search out all the land."',
        4: 'But the woman had taken the two men and hidden them, and she said, "Yes, the men came to me, but I did not know where they were from.',
        5: 'And it came about when the gate was about to be shut, at dark, that the men went out. I do not know where the men went. Pursue them quickly, for you will overtake them."',
        6: 'But she had brought them up to the roof and hidden them in the stalks of flax which she had laid in order on the roof.',
        7: 'So the men pursued them on the road to the Jordan to the fords, and the gate was shut as soon as the pursuers had gone out after them.',
        8: 'Now before they lay down, she came up to them on the roof,',
        9: 'and said to the men, "I know that the LORD has given you the land, and that the terror of you has fallen on us, and that all the inhabitants of the land have melted away before you.',
        10: 'For we have heard how the LORD dried up the water of the Red Sea before you when you came out of Egypt, and what you did to the two kings of the Amorites who were beyond the Jordan, to Sihon and to Og, whom you utterly destroyed.',
        11: 'And when we heard it, our hearts melted and no courage remained in any man any longer because of you; for the LORD your God, He is God in heaven above and on earth beneath.',
        12: 'Now therefore, please swear to me by the LORD, since I have dealt kindly with you, that you also will deal kindly with my father\'s household, and give me a pledge of truth,',
        13: 'and spare my father and my mother and my brothers and my sisters, with all who belong to them, and deliver our lives from death."',
        14: 'So the men said to her, "Our life for yours if you do not tell this business of ours! And it shall come about when the LORD gives us the land, that we will deal kindly and faithfully with you."',
        15: 'Then she let them down by a rope through the window, for her house was on the city wall, so that she was living on the wall.',
        16: 'And she said to them, "Go to the hill country, so that the pursuers will not find you, and hide yourselves there for three days until the pursuers return. Then afterward you may go your way."',
        17: 'And the men said to her, "We shall be free from this oath to you which you have made us swear,',
        18: 'unless, when we come into the land, you tie this cord of scarlet thread in the window through which you let us down, and gather to yourself into the house your father and your mother and your brothers and all your father\'s household.',
        19: 'And it shall be that anyone who goes out of the doors of your house into the street, his blood shall be on his own head, and we shall be guiltless. But anyone who is with you in the house, his blood shall be on our head if a hand is laid on him.',
        20: 'But if you tell this business of ours, then we shall be free from the oath which you have made us swear."',
        21: 'And she said, "According to your words, so be it." And she sent them away, and they departed. And she tied the scarlet cord in the window.',
        22: 'And they went and came to the hill country, and stayed there three days until the pursuers returned. And the pursuers searched all along the road but did not find them.',
        23: 'Then the two men returned and came down from the hill country and crossed over and came to Joshua the son of Nun, and they related to him all that had happened to them.',
        24: 'And they said to Joshua, "Surely the LORD has given all the land into our hands; moreover, all the inhabitants of the land have melted away before us."',
    },
    3: {  # Chapter 3
        1: 'Then Joshua rose early in the morning, and he and all the sons of Israel set out from Shittim and came to the Jordan, and they lodged there before they crossed over.',
        2: 'And it came about at the end of three days, that the officers went through the midst of the camp,',
        3: 'and they commanded the people, saying, "When you see the ark of the covenant of the LORD your God with the Levitical priests carrying it, then you shall set out from your place and go after it.',
        4: 'However, there shall be a distance between you and it of about two thousand cubits by measure. Do not come near it, so that you may know the way by which you shall go, for you have not passed this way before."',
        5: 'Then Joshua said to the people, "Consecrate yourselves, for tomorrow the LORD will do wonders among you."',
        6: 'And Joshua spoke to the priests, saying, "Take up the ark of the covenant and cross over ahead of the people." So they took up the ark of the covenant and went ahead of the people.',
        7: 'Now the LORD said to Joshua, "This day I will begin to exalt you in the sight of all Israel, that they may know that just as I was with Moses, so I will be with you.',
        8: 'You shall, moreover, command the priests who carry the ark of the covenant, saying, \'When you come to the edge of the waters of the Jordan, you shall stand still in the Jordan.\'"',
        9: 'Then Joshua said to the sons of Israel, "Come here, and hear the words of the LORD your God."',
        10: 'And Joshua said, "By this you shall know that the living God is among you, and that He will assuredly drive out from before you the Canaanite, the Hittite, the Hivite, the Perizzite, the Girgashite, the Amorite, and the Jebusite.',
        11: 'Behold, the ark of the covenant of the Lord of all the earth is crossing over ahead of you into the Jordan.',
        12: 'Now then, take for yourselves twelve men from the tribes of Israel, one man for each tribe.',
        13: 'And it shall come about, as soon as the soles of the feet of the priests who carry the ark of the LORD, the Lord of all the earth, rest in the waters of the Jordan, the waters of the Jordan shall be cut off, and the waters that are flowing down from above shall stand in one heap."',
        14: 'So when the people set out from their tents to cross over the Jordan, with the priests carrying the ark of the covenant before the people,',
        15: 'and when those who carried the ark came to the Jordan, and the feet of the priests carrying the ark were dipped in the edge of the water -- now the Jordan overflows all its banks all the days of harvest --',
        16: 'the waters which were flowing down from above stood and rose up in one heap, a great distance away at Adam, the city that is beside Zarethan; and those flowing down toward the sea of the Arabah, the Salt Sea, were completely cut off. So the people crossed over opposite Jericho.',
        17: 'And the priests who carried the ark of the covenant of the LORD stood firm on dry ground in the middle of the Jordan while all Israel was crossing over on dry ground, until all the nation had finished crossing over the Jordan.',
    },
    4: {  # Chapter 4
        1: 'Now when all the nation had finished crossing over the Jordan, the LORD spoke to Joshua, saying,',
        2: '"Take for yourselves twelve men from the people, one man from each tribe,',
        3: 'and command them, saying, \'Take up for yourselves twelve stones from here, out of the middle of the Jordan, from the place where the priests\' feet stood firm, and carry them over with you and set them down in the lodging place where you will lodge tonight.\'"',
        4: 'So Joshua called the twelve men whom he had appointed from the sons of Israel, one man from each tribe;',
        5: 'and Joshua said to them, "Cross over before the ark of the LORD your God into the middle of the Jordan, and each of you take up a stone on his shoulder, according to the number of the tribes of the sons of Israel,',
        6: 'so that this may be a sign among you. When your children ask in time to come, saying, \'What do these stones mean to you?\'',
        7: 'then you shall say to them, \'Because the waters of the Jordan were cut off before the ark of the covenant of the LORD; when it crossed over the Jordan, the waters of the Jordan were cut off.\' So these stones shall become a memorial to the sons of Israel forever."',
        8: 'And the sons of Israel did so, just as Joshua commanded. And they took up twelve stones from the middle of the Jordan, just as the LORD spoke to Joshua, according to the number of the tribes of the sons of Israel; and they carried them over with them to the lodging place, and set them down there.',
        9: 'Then Joshua set up twelve stones in the middle of the Jordan at the place where the feet of the priests who carried the ark of the covenant were standing, and they are there to this day.',
        10: 'For the priests who carried the ark were standing in the middle of the Jordan until everything was completed that the LORD had commanded Joshua to speak to the people, according to all that Moses had commanded Joshua. And the people hurried and crossed over.',
        11: 'And it came about when all the people had finished crossing over, that the ark of the LORD and the priests crossed over in the presence of the people.',
        12: 'And the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh crossed over in battle array before the sons of Israel, just as Moses had spoken to them.',
        13: 'About forty thousand equipped for war crossed over before the LORD to the desert plains of Jericho for battle.',
        14: 'On that day the LORD exalted Joshua in the sight of all Israel; and they revered him, just as they had revered Moses, all the days of his life.',
        15: 'Now the LORD said to Joshua,',
        16: '"Command the priests who carry the ark of the testimony to come up from the Jordan."',
        17: 'So Joshua commanded the priests, saying, "Come up from the Jordan."',
        18: 'And it came about when the priests who carried the ark of the covenant of the LORD came up from the middle of the Jordan, and the soles of the priests\' feet were lifted up to the dry ground, that the waters of the Jordan returned to their place and went over all its banks as before.',
        19: 'Now the people came up from the Jordan on the tenth day of the first month and camped at Gilgal on the eastern edge of Jericho.',
        20: 'And those twelve stones which they had taken from the Jordan, Joshua set up at Gilgal.',
        21: 'And he said to the sons of Israel, "When your children ask their fathers in time to come, saying, \'What are these stones?\'',
        22: 'then you shall inform your children, saying, \'Israel crossed over this Jordan on dry ground.\'',
        23: 'For the LORD your God dried up the waters of the Jordan before you until you had crossed over, just as the LORD your God had done to the Red Sea, which He dried up before us until we had crossed over,',
        24: 'so that all the peoples of the earth may know that the hand of the LORD is mighty, so that you may fear the LORD your God forever."',
    },
    5: {  # Chapter 5
        1: 'Now it came about when all the kings of the Amorites who were beyond the Jordan to the west, and all the kings of the Canaanites who were by the sea, heard that the LORD had dried up the waters of the Jordan before the sons of Israel until they had crossed over, that their hearts melted, and there was no spirit in them any longer because of the sons of Israel.',
        2: 'At that time the LORD said to Joshua, "Make for yourself flint knives and circumcise again the sons of Israel a second time."',
        3: 'So Joshua made himself flint knives and circumcised the sons of Israel at the hill of the foreskins.',
        4: 'And this is the reason why Joshua circumcised them: all the people who came out of Egypt who were males, all the men of war, died in the wilderness along the way after they came out of Egypt.',
        5: 'For all the people who came out were circumcised, but all the people who were born in the wilderness along the way as they came out of Egypt had not been circumcised.',
        6: 'For the sons of Israel walked forty years in the wilderness, until all the nation, that is, the men of war who came out of Egypt, perished because they did not listen to the voice of the LORD, to whom the LORD had sworn that He would not let them see the land which the LORD had sworn to their fathers to give us, a land flowing with milk and honey.',
        7: 'And their sons whom He raised up in their place, Joshua circumcised; for they were uncircumcised, because they had not been circumcised along the way.',
        8: 'Now when they had finished circumcising all the nation, they remained in their places in the camp until they were healed.',
        9: 'Then the LORD said to Joshua, "Today I have rolled away the reproach of Egypt from you." So the name of that place is called Gilgal to this day.',
        10: 'While the sons of Israel camped at Gilgal, they observed the Passover on the evening of the fourteenth day of the month on the desert plains of Jericho.',
        11: 'And on the day after the Passover, on that very day, they ate some of the produce of the land, unleavened cakes and parched grain.',
        12: 'And the manna ceased on the day after they had eaten some of the produce of the land, so that the sons of Israel no longer had manna, but they ate some of the yield of the land of Canaan during that year.',
        13: 'Now it came about when Joshua was by Jericho, that he lifted up his eyes and looked, and behold, a man was standing opposite him with his sword drawn in his hand, and Joshua went to him and said to him, "Are you for us or for our adversaries?"',
        14: 'And he said, "No; rather I indeed come now as commander of the army of the LORD." And Joshua fell on his face to the earth and bowed down, and said to him, "What does my lord say to his servant?"',
        15: 'And the commander of the army of the LORD said to Joshua, "Remove your sandals from your feet, for the place where you are standing is holy." And Joshua did so.',
    },
    6: {  # Chapter 6
        1: 'Now Jericho was tightly shut up because of the sons of Israel; no one went out and no one came in.',
        2: 'And the LORD said to Joshua, "See, I have given Jericho into your hand, with its king and the mighty men of valor.',
        3: 'And you shall march around the city, all the men of war circling the city once. Thus you shall do for six days.',
        4: 'Also seven priests shall carry seven trumpets of rams\' horns before the ark. Then on the seventh day you shall march around the city seven times, and the priests shall blow the trumpets.',
        5: 'And it shall be that when they make a long blast with the ram\'s horn, and when you hear the sound of the trumpet, all the people shall shout with a great shout; and the wall of the city shall fall down flat, and the people shall go up, every man straight ahead."',
        6: 'So Joshua the son of Nun called the priests and said to them, "Take up the ark of the covenant, and let seven priests carry seven trumpets of rams\' horns before the ark of the LORD."',
        7: 'Then he said to the people, "Go forward and march around the city, and let the armed men pass on before the ark of the LORD."',
        8: 'And it was so, that when Joshua had spoken to the people, the seven priests carrying the seven trumpets of rams\' horns before the LORD went forward and blew the trumpets, and the ark of the covenant of the LORD followed them.',
        9: 'And the armed men went before the priests who blew the trumpets, and the rear guard came after the ark, while they continued to blow the trumpets.',
        10: 'But Joshua commanded the people, saying, "You shall not shout nor let your voice be heard, nor shall any word proceed out of your mouth, until the day I tell you, \'Shout!\' Then you shall shout."',
        11: 'So he had the ark of the LORD go around the city, circling it once; then they came into the camp and spent the night in the camp.',
        12: 'Now Joshua rose early in the morning, and the priests took up the ark of the LORD.',
        13: 'And the seven priests carrying the seven trumpets of rams\' horns before the ark of the LORD went on continually and blew the trumpets; and the armed men went before them, and the rear guard came after the ark of the LORD, while they continued to blow the trumpets.',
        14: 'Thus the second day they marched around the city once and returned to the camp. They did so for six days.',
        15: 'Then on the seventh day they rose early at the dawning of the day and marched around the city in the same manner seven times; only on that day did they march around the city seven times.',
        16: 'And it came about at the seventh time, when the priests blew the trumpets, Joshua said to the people, "Shout! For the LORD has given you the city.',
        17: 'And the city shall be under the ban, it and all that is in it belongs to the LORD; only Rahab the prostitute and all who are with her in the house shall live, because she hid the messengers whom we sent.',
        18: 'But as for you, only keep yourselves from the things under the ban, so that you do not covet and take some of the things under the ban, and make the camp of Israel accursed and bring trouble on it.',
        19: 'But all the silver and gold and articles of bronze and iron are holy to the LORD; they shall go into the treasury of the LORD."',
        20: 'So the people shouted, and the trumpets were blown. And it came about when the people heard the sound of the trumpet, that the people shouted with a great shout, and the wall fell down flat, so that the people went up into the city, every man straight ahead, and they captured the city.',
        21: 'And they utterly destroyed everything in the city, both man and woman, young and old, and ox and sheep and donkey, with the edge of the sword.',
        22: 'And Joshua said to the two men who had spied out the land, "Go into the house of the prostitute, and bring the woman out from there and all who belong to her, as you swore to her."',
        23: 'So the young men who were spies went in and brought out Rahab and her father and her mother and her brothers and all who belonged to her; they also brought out all her relatives and placed them outside the camp of Israel.',
        24: 'And they burned the city with fire, and all that was in it. Only the silver and the gold and the articles of bronze and iron they put into the treasury of the house of the LORD.',
        25: 'However, Rahab the prostitute and her father\'s household and all who belonged to her, Joshua spared; and she has lived in the midst of Israel to this day, for she hid the messengers whom Joshua sent to spy out Jericho.',
        26: 'Then Joshua made them take an oath at that time, saying, "Cursed before the LORD is the man who rises up and builds this city Jericho; with the loss of his firstborn he shall lay its foundation, and with the loss of his youngest son he shall set up its gates."',
        27: 'So the LORD was with Joshua, and his fame was in all the land.',
    },
    7: {  # Chapter 7
        1: 'But the sons of Israel acted unfaithfully regarding the things under the ban, for Achan the son of Carmi, the son of Zabdi, the son of Zerah, from the tribe of Judah, took some of the things under the ban; and the anger of the LORD burned against the sons of Israel.',
        2: 'And Joshua sent men from Jericho to Ai, which is near Beth-aven, east of Bethel, and he spoke to them, saying, "Go up and spy out the land." So the men went up and spied out Ai.',
        3: 'And they returned to Joshua and said to him, "Do not let all the people go up; let about two thousand or three thousand men go up and strike Ai. Do not weary all the people there, for they are few."',
        4: 'So about three thousand men from the people went up there, but they fled before the men of Ai.',
        5: 'And the men of Ai struck down about thirty-six of their men, and they pursued them from before the gate as far as Shebarim and struck them down on the descent. And the heart of the people melted and became like water.',
        6: 'Then Joshua tore his garments and fell on his face to the earth before the ark of the LORD until the evening, both he and the elders of Israel, and they put dust on their heads.',
        7: 'And Joshua said, "Alas, O Lord GOD, why have You brought this people over the Jordan at all, only to give us into the hand of the Amorites, to destroy us? If only we had been willing to dwell beyond the Jordan!"',
        8: '"O Lord, what can I say after Israel has turned its back before its enemies?"',
        9: '"For the Canaanites and all the inhabitants of the land will hear of it, and they will surround us and cut off our name from the earth. And what will You do for Your great name?"',
        10: 'And the LORD said to Joshua, "Rise up! Why is it that you have fallen on your face?"',
        11: '"Israel has sinned, and they have also transgressed My covenant which I commanded them, and they have also taken some of the things under the ban, and have also stolen, and have also deceived, and have also put them among their own possessions."',
        12: '"Therefore the sons of Israel cannot stand before their enemies; they turn their backs before their enemies, for they have become accursed. I will not be with you anymore unless you destroy the things under the ban from your midst."',
        13: '"Rise up! Consecrate the people and say, \'Consecrate yourselves for tomorrow, for thus says the LORD, the God of Israel: There are things under the ban in your midst, O Israel. You cannot stand before your enemies until you remove the things under the ban from your midst.\'"',
        14: '"And in the morning you shall come near by your tribes, and it shall be that the tribe which the LORD takes by lot shall come near by clans, and the clan which the LORD takes shall come near by households, and the household which the LORD takes shall come near man by man."',
        15: '"And it shall be that the one who is taken with the things under the ban shall be burned with fire, he and all that belongs to him, because he has transgressed the covenant of the LORD, and because he has done a disgraceful thing in Israel."',
        16: 'So Joshua rose early in the morning and brought Israel near by their tribes, and the tribe of Judah was taken.',
        17: 'And he brought near the clan of Judah, and the clan of the Zerahites was taken. And he brought near the clan of the Zerahites man by man, and Zabdi was taken.',
        18: 'And he brought near his household man by man, and Achan the son of Carmi, the son of Zabdi, the son of Zerah, from the tribe of Judah, was taken.',
        19: 'Then Joshua said to Achan, "My son, please give glory to the LORD, the God of Israel, and give praise to Him. And tell me now what you have done; do not hide it from me."',
        20: 'And Achan answered Joshua and said, "Truly, I have sinned against the LORD, the God of Israel, and this is what I have done:"',
        21: '"When I saw among the spoil a beautiful mantle from Shinar, and two hundred shekels of silver, and one bar of gold of fifty shekels weight, then I coveted them and took them. And behold, they are hidden in the earth inside my tent, with the silver underneath it."',
        22: 'So Joshua sent messengers, and they ran to the tent; and behold, it was hidden in his tent, with the silver underneath it.',
        23: 'And they took them from inside the tent and brought them to Joshua and to all the sons of Israel, and they poured them out before the LORD.',
        24: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, took Achan the son of Zerah, and the silver, and the mantle, and the bar of gold, and his sons, and his daughters, and his ox, and his donkey, and his sheep, and his tent, and all that belonged to him, and they brought them up to the Valley of Achor.',
        25: 'And Joshua said, "Why have you brought trouble on us? The LORD will trouble you this day." And all Israel stoned him with stones, and they burned them with fire and stoned them with stones.',
        26: 'And they raised over him a great heap of stones to this day. And the LORD turned from the fierceness of His anger. Therefore the name of that place has been called the Valley of Achor to this day.',
    },
    8: {  # Chapter 8
        1: 'Then the LORD said to Joshua, "Do not fear and do not be dismayed. Take all the people of war with you and arise, go up to Ai. See, I have given into your hand the king of Ai, and his people, and his city, and his land."',
        2: '"And you shall do to Ai and its king as you did to Jericho and its king. Only its spoil and its livestock you shall take as plunder for yourselves. Set an ambush for the city behind it."',
        3: 'So Joshua and all the people of war arose to go up to Ai. And Joshua chose thirty thousand men, mighty men of valor, and sent them out by night.',
        4: 'And he commanded them, saying, "See, you are going to lie in ambush against the city, behind the city. Do not go very far from the city, but all of you be ready."',
        5: '"And I, and all the people who are with me, will approach the city. And it shall be that when they come out to meet us as at the first, we will flee before them."',
        6: '"And they will come out after us until we have drawn them away from the city, for they will say, \'They are fleeing before us as at the first.\' So we will flee before them."',
        7: '"Then you shall rise from the ambush and take possession of the city, for the LORD your God will give it into your hand."',
        8: '"And it shall be, when you have seized the city, that you shall set the city on fire. According to the word of the LORD you shall do. See, I have commanded you."',
        9: 'So Joshua sent them out, and they went to the place of ambush and stayed between Bethel and Ai, on the west side of Ai. But Joshua spent that night among the people.',
        10: 'And Joshua rose early in the morning and mustered the people, and he and the elders of Israel went up before the people to Ai.',
        11: 'And all the people of war who were with him went up and drew near and came before the city, and they camped on the north side of Ai. Now there was a valley between him and Ai.',
        12: 'And he took about five thousand men and set them in ambush between Bethel and Ai, on the west side of the city.',
        13: 'So they stationed the people, all the camp that was on the north side of the city, and its rear guard on the west side of the city. And Joshua went that night into the midst of the valley.',
        14: 'And it came about when the king of Ai saw it, that the men of the city hurried and rose early and went out to meet Israel in battle, he and all his people, at the appointed place before the Arabah. But he did not know that there was an ambush against him behind the city.',
        15: 'And Joshua and all Israel let themselves be beaten before them and fled by the way of the wilderness.',
        16: 'And all the people who were in the city were called together to pursue them, and they pursued Joshua and were drawn away from the city.',
        17: 'And not a man was left in Ai or Bethel who had not gone out after Israel, and they left the city open and pursued Israel.',
        18: 'Then the LORD said to Joshua, "Stretch out the javelin that is in your hand toward Ai, for I will give it into your hand." So Joshua stretched out the javelin that was in his hand toward the city.',
        19: 'And the men in ambush rose quickly from their place, and they ran as soon as he stretched out his hand and entered the city and captured it; and they hurried and set the city on fire.',
        20: 'And the men of Ai turned back and looked, and behold, the smoke of the city was ascending to the sky, and they had no power to flee this way or that, for the people who had fled to the wilderness turned back against the pursuers.',
        21: 'And when Joshua and all Israel saw that the men in ambush had captured the city and that the smoke of the city was ascending, then they turned back and struck the men of Ai.',
        22: 'And the others came out from the city to meet them, so they were in the midst of Israel, some on this side and some on that side. And they struck them until no survivor or fugitive remained.',
        23: 'But the king of Ai they captured alive and brought him to Joshua.',
        24: 'And it came about when Israel had finished killing all the inhabitants of Ai in the field, in the wilderness where they pursued them, and all of them had fallen by the edge of the sword until they were consumed, then all Israel returned to Ai and struck it with the edge of the sword.',
        25: 'And all who fell that day, both men and women, were twelve thousand — all the people of Ai.',
        26: 'And Joshua did not draw back his hand with which he stretched out the javelin until he had utterly destroyed all the inhabitants of Ai.',
        27: 'Only the livestock and the spoil of that city Israel took as plunder for themselves, according to the word of the LORD which He had commanded Joshua.',
        28: 'So Joshua burned Ai and made it a heap forever, a desolation to this day.',
        29: 'And the king of Ai he hanged on a tree until the time of evening. And at the setting of the sun, Joshua commanded, and they took his body down from the tree and threw it at the entrance of the gate of the city, and raised over it a great heap of stones to this day.',
        30: 'Then Joshua built an altar to the LORD, the God of Israel, on Mount Ebal,',
        31: 'just as Moses the servant of the LORD had commanded the sons of Israel, as it is written in the book of the law of Moses: "an altar of uncut stones on which no man has wielded an iron tool." And they offered on it burnt offerings to the LORD and sacrificed peace offerings.',
        32: 'And he wrote there on the stones a copy of the law of Moses, which he had written, in the presence of the sons of Israel.',
        33: 'And all Israel, with their elders, and officers, and their judges, were standing on both sides of the ark before the Levitical priests who carried the ark of the covenant of the LORD, the sojourner as well as the native-born, half of them in front of Mount Gerizim and half of them in front of Mount Ebal, just as Moses the servant of the LORD had commanded at first, to bless the people of Israel.',
        34: 'And afterward he read all the words of the law, the blessing and the curse, according to all that is written in the book of the law.',
        35: 'There was not a word of all that Moses had commanded which Joshua did not read before all the assembly of Israel, including the women and the little ones and the sojourners who walked among them.',
    },
    9: {  # Chapter 9
        1: 'And it came about when all the kings who were beyond the Jordan, in the hill country and in the lowland and on all the coast of the Great Sea toward Lebanon — the Hittite and the Amorite, the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite — heard of this,',
        2: 'that they gathered themselves together with one accord to fight with Joshua and with Israel.',
        3: 'But the inhabitants of Gibeon heard what Joshua had done to Jericho and to Ai,',
        4: 'and they also acted with cunning and went and made provision for a journey. And they took worn-out sacks on their donkeys, and worn-out wineskins, torn and mended,',
        5: 'and worn-out and patched sandals on their feet, and worn-out garments on themselves; and all the bread of their provision was dry and had become crumbled.',
        6: 'And they went to Joshua, to the camp at Gilgal, and said to him and to the men of Israel, "We have come from a far country; now therefore, make a covenant with us."',
        7: 'And the men of Israel said to the Hivites, "Perhaps you are living in our midst; how then can we make a covenant with you?"',
        8: 'But they said to Joshua, "We are your servants." And Joshua said to them, "Who are you, and where do you come from?"',
        9: 'And they said to him, "Your servants have come from a very far country because of the name of the LORD your God, for we have heard the report of Him and all that He did in Egypt,"',
        10: '"and all that He did to the two kings of the Amorites who were beyond the Jordan, to Sihon king of Heshbon and to Og king of Bashan, who was at Ashtaroth."',
        11: '"So our elders and all the inhabitants of our country spoke to us, saying, \'Take provisions in your hand for the journey, and go to meet them and say to them, "We are your servants; now therefore, make a covenant with us."\'"',
        12: '"This bread of ours was warm when we took it as our provision from our houses on the day we set out to come to you; but now behold, it is dry and has become crumbled."',
        13: '"And these wineskins which we filled were new; and behold, they are torn. And these our garments and our sandals are worn out from the very long journey."',
        14: 'So the men took some of their provision, but they did not ask for the counsel of the LORD.',
        15: 'And Joshua made peace with them and made a covenant with them, to let them live; and the leaders of the congregation swore an oath to them.',
        16: 'And it came about at the end of three days after they had made a covenant with them, that they heard that they were neighbors and that they were living in their midst.',
        17: 'Then the sons of Israel set out and came to their cities on the third day. Now their cities were Gibeon and Chephirah and Beeroth and Kiriath-jearim.',
        18: 'And the sons of Israel did not strike them because the leaders of the congregation had sworn to them by the LORD, the God of Israel. And the whole congregation grumbled against the leaders.',
        19: 'But all the leaders said to the whole congregation, "We have sworn to them by the LORD, the God of Israel, and now we cannot touch them."',
        20: '"This we will do to them: we will let them live, so that wrath will not be upon us for the oath which we swore to them."',
        21: 'And the leaders said to them, "Let them live." So they became cutters of wood and drawers of water for the whole congregation, just as the leaders had spoken to them.',
        22: 'Then Joshua called for them and spoke to them, saying, "Why have you deceived us, saying, \'We are very far from you,\' when you are living in our midst?"',
        23: '"Now therefore, you are cursed, and you shall never cease being slaves, both cutters of wood and drawers of water for the house of my God."',
        24: 'And they answered Joshua and said, "Because it was surely told to your servants that the LORD your God commanded His servant Moses to give you all the land, and to destroy all the inhabitants of the land before you; so we feared greatly for our lives because of you, and we did this thing."',
        25: '"And now behold, we are in your hand; do as it seems good and right in your eyes to do to us."',
        26: 'So he did thus to them, and delivered them from the hand of the sons of Israel, and they did not kill them.',
        27: 'But Joshua made them that day cutters of wood and drawers of water for the congregation and for the altar of the LORD, to this day, in the place which He would choose.',
    },
    10: {  # Chapter 10
        1: 'And it came about when Adoni-zedek king of Jerusalem heard that Joshua had captured Ai and had utterly destroyed it — as he had done to Jericho and its king, so he had done to Ai and its king — and that the inhabitants of Gibeon had made peace with Israel and were in their midst,',
        2: 'that he feared greatly, because Gibeon was a great city, like one of the royal cities, and because it was greater than Ai, and all its men were mighty.',
        3: 'Therefore Adoni-zedek king of Jerusalem sent word to Hoham king of Hebron, and to Piram king of Jarmuth, and to Japhia king of Lachish, and to Debir king of Eglon, saying,',
        4: '"Come up to me and help me, and let us strike Gibeon, for it has made peace with Joshua and with the sons of Israel."',
        5: 'So the five kings of the Amorites — the king of Jerusalem, the king of Hebron, the king of Jarmuth, the king of Lachish, the king of Eglon — gathered together and went up, they and all their armies, and they camped against Gibeon and fought against it.',
        6: 'And the men of Gibeon sent word to Joshua, to the camp at Gilgal, saying, "Do not let your hands drop from your servants; come up to us quickly and save us and help us, for all the kings of the Amorites who live in the hill country have assembled against us."',
        7: 'So Joshua went up from Gilgal, he and all the people of war with him, and all the mighty men of valor.',
        8: 'And the LORD said to Joshua, "Do not fear them, for I have given them into your hand; not a man of them shall stand before you."',
        9: 'So Joshua came upon them suddenly; he marched all night from Gilgal.',
        10: 'And the LORD threw them into confusion before Israel, and He struck them with a great slaughter at Gibeon, and pursued them by the way of the ascent of Beth-horon and struck them as far as Azekah and Makkedah.',
        11: 'And it came about as they fled before Israel, while they were at the descent of Beth-horon, that the LORD threw great stones from heaven on them as far as Azekah, and they died. More died from the hailstones than those whom the sons of Israel killed with the sword.',
        12: 'Then Joshua spoke to the LORD in the day when the LORD gave the Amorites over before the sons of Israel, and he said in the sight of Israel, "Sun, be still over Gibeon, and moon, over the valley of Aijalon!"',
        13: 'And the sun was still, and the moon stopped, until the nation had avenged itself on its enemies. Is this not written in the Book of Jasher? And the sun stopped in the middle of the sky and did not hasten to go down for about a whole day.',
        14: 'And there was no day like that before it or after it, when the LORD listened to the voice of a man, for the LORD fought for Israel.',
        15: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, returned to the camp at Gilgal.',
        16: 'Now the five kings had fled and hidden themselves in the cave at Makkedah.',
        17: 'And it was reported to Joshua, saying, "The five kings have been found hidden in the cave at Makkedah."',
        18: 'And Joshua said, "Roll large stones against the mouth of the cave and station men by it to guard them."',
        19: '"But you, do not stay; pursue your enemies and attack them from the rear. Do not allow them to enter their cities, for the LORD your God has given them into your hand."',
        20: 'And it came about when Joshua and the sons of Israel had finished striking them with a very great slaughter until they were consumed, and the survivors among them had entered the fortified cities,',
        21: 'that all the people returned to the camp, to Joshua at Makkedah, in peace. No one spoke a word against any of the sons of Israel.',
        22: 'Then Joshua said, "Open the mouth of the cave and bring out those five kings to me from the cave."',
        23: 'And they did so, and brought out those five kings to him from the cave: the king of Jerusalem, the king of Hebron, the king of Jarmuth, the king of Lachish, and the king of Eglon.',
        24: 'And it came about when they brought out those kings to Joshua, that Joshua called for all the men of Israel and said to the commanders of the men of war who had gone with him, "Come near, put your feet on the necks of these kings." So they came near and put their feet on their necks.',
        25: 'Then Joshua said to them, "Do not fear or be dismayed; be strong and courageous, for thus the LORD will do to all your enemies with whom you fight."',
        26: 'And afterward Joshua struck them and put them to death and hanged them on five trees; and they hung on the trees until evening.',
        27: 'And it came about at the time of the setting of the sun that Joshua commanded, and they took them down from the trees and threw them into the cave where they had hidden themselves, and placed large stones over the mouth of the cave, to this very day.',
        28: 'And Joshua captured Makkedah on that day and struck it with the edge of the sword, and he utterly destroyed its king and every person who was in it; he left no survivor. And he did to the king of Makkedah just as he had done to the king of Jericho.',
        29: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, passed on from Makkedah to Libnah and fought against Libnah.',
        30: 'And the LORD gave it also, with its king, into the hand of Israel, and he struck it with the edge of the sword and every person who was in it; he left no survivor in it. And he did to its king just as he had done to the king of Jericho.',
        31: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, passed on from Libnah to Lachish and camped against it and fought against it.',
        32: 'And the LORD gave Lachish into the hand of Israel, and he captured it on the second day, and struck it with the edge of the sword and every person who was in it, just as he had done to Libnah.',
        33: 'Then Horam king of Gezer came up to help Lachish, and Joshua struck him and his people until he had left him no survivor.',
        34: 'And Joshua, and all Israel with him, passed on from Lachish to Eglon, and they camped against it and fought against it.',
        35: 'And they captured it on that day and struck it with the edge of the sword; and he utterly destroyed every person who was in it that day, just as he had done to Lachish.',
        36: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, went up from Eglon to Hebron, and they fought against it.',
        37: 'And they captured it and struck it with the edge of the sword, and its king and all its cities, and every person who was in it; he left no survivor, just as he had done to Eglon. And he utterly destroyed it and every person who was in it.',
        38: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, turned back to Debir and fought against it.',
        39: 'And he captured it, and its king, and all its cities, and they struck them with the edge of the sword and utterly destroyed every person who was in it; he left no survivor. Just as he had done to Hebron, so he did to Debir and its king, and just as he had done to Libnah and its king.',
        40: 'So Joshua struck all the land: the hill country and the Negev and the lowland and the slopes, and all their kings. He left no survivor, but he utterly destroyed every breathing thing, just as the LORD, the God of Israel, had commanded.',
        41: 'And Joshua struck them from Kadesh-barnea as far as Gaza, and all the land of Goshen as far as Gibeon.',
        42: 'And Joshua captured all these kings and their land at one time, because the LORD, the God of Israel, fought for Israel.',
        43: 'Then Joshua, and all Israel with him, returned to the camp at Gilgal.',
    },
    11: {  # Chapter 11
        1: 'And it came about when Jabin king of Hazor heard of it, that he sent word to Jobab king of Madon, and to the king of Shimron, and to the king of Achshaph,',
        2: 'and to the kings who were in the north, in the hill country, and in the Arabah south of Chinneroth, and in the lowland, and on the heights of Dor on the west,',
        3: 'to the Canaanite on the east and on the west, and the Amorite and the Hittite and the Perizzite and the Jebusite in the hill country, and the Hivite at the foot of Hermon in the land of Mizpah.',
        4: 'And they came out, they and all their armies with them, as many people as the sand that is on the seashore in abundance, with very many horses and chariots.',
        5: 'And all these kings met together, and they came and camped together at the waters of Merom to fight against Israel.',
        6: 'Then the LORD said to Joshua, "Do not be afraid because of them, for tomorrow at this time I will give all of them slain before Israel; you shall hamstring their horses and burn their chariots with fire."',
        7: 'So Joshua and all the people of war with him came against them suddenly at the waters of Merom and fell upon them.',
        8: 'And the LORD gave them into the hand of Israel, and they struck them and pursued them as far as Great Sidon and Misrephoth-maim and the valley of Mizpeh to the east; and they struck them until no survivor was left to them.',
        9: 'And Joshua did to them just as the LORD had told him: he hamstrung their horses and burned their chariots with fire.',
        10: 'Then Joshua turned back at that time and captured Hazor and struck its king with the sword, for Hazor formerly was the head of all these kingdoms.',
        11: 'And they struck every person who was in it with the edge of the sword, utterly destroying them. There was no one left who breathed. And he burned Hazor with fire.',
        12: 'And Joshua captured all the cities of these kings and all their kings, and he struck them with the edge of the sword. He utterly destroyed them, just as Moses the servant of the LORD had commanded.',
        13: 'But as for the cities that stood on their mounds, Israel burned none of them, except Hazor alone, which Joshua burned.',
        14: 'And all the spoil of these cities and the livestock, the sons of Israel took as their plunder; but every man they struck with the edge of the sword until they had destroyed them. They did not leave any who breathed.',
        15: 'Just as the LORD had commanded Moses His servant, so Moses commanded Joshua, and so Joshua did. He left nothing undone of all that the LORD had commanded Moses.',
        16: 'So Joshua took all that land: the hill country, and all the Negev, and all the land of Goshen, and the lowland, and the Arabah, and the hill country of Israel and its lowland,',
        17: 'from Mount Halak, which goes up to Seir, as far as Baal-gad in the valley of Lebanon at the foot of Mount Hermon. And he captured all their kings and struck them and put them to death.',
        18: 'Joshua made war a long time with all those kings.',
        19: 'There was not a city that made peace with the sons of Israel except the Hivites living in Gibeon; they took them all in battle.',
        20: 'For it was of the LORD to harden their hearts, to meet Israel in battle, in order that He might utterly destroy them, that they might receive no mercy, but that He might destroy them, just as the LORD had commanded Moses.',
        21: 'Then Joshua came at that time and cut off the Anakim from the hill country, from Hebron, from Debir, from Anab, and from all the hill country of Judah, and from all the hill country of Israel. Joshua utterly destroyed them with their cities.',
        22: 'No Anakim were left in the land of the sons of Israel; only in Gaza, in Gath, and in Ashdod some remained.',
        23: 'So Joshua took the whole land, according to all that the LORD had spoken to Moses, and Joshua gave it as an inheritance to Israel according to their divisions by their tribes. And the land had rest from war.',
    },
    12: {  # Chapter 12
        1: 'Now these are the kings of the land whom the sons of Israel struck and whose land they possessed beyond the Jordan toward the rising of the sun, from the valley of the Arnon as far as Mount Hermon, and all the Arabah to the east:',
        2: 'Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived in Heshbon and ruled from Aroer, which is on the edge of the valley of the Arnon, both the middle of the valley and half of Gilead, as far as the brook Jabbok, the border of the sons of Ammon;',
        3: 'and the Arabah as far as the Sea of Chinneroth toward the east, and as far as the sea of the Arabah, the Salt Sea, toward the east, the way to Beth-jeshimoth, and on the south, at the foot of the slopes of Pisgah;',
        4: 'and the territory of Og king of Bashan, one of the remnant of the Rephaim, who lived at Ashtaroth and at Edrei,',
        5: 'and he ruled over Mount Hermon and Salecah and all Bashan, as far as the border of the Geshurites and the Maacathites, and half of Gilead, as far as the border of Sihon king of Heshbon.',
        6: 'Moses the servant of the LORD and the sons of Israel struck them, and Moses the servant of the LORD gave their land as a possession to the Reubenites and the Gadites and the half-tribe of Manasseh.',
        7: 'And these are the kings of the land whom Joshua and the sons of Israel struck beyond the Jordan on the west, from Baal-gad in the valley of Lebanon as far as Mount Halak, which goes up to Seir; and Joshua gave it to the tribes of Israel as a possession according to their divisions,',
        8: 'in the hill country and in the lowland and in the Arabah and on the slopes and in the wilderness and in the Negev — the Hittite, the Amorite, and the Canaanite, the Perizzite, the Hivite, and the Jebusite:',
        9: 'the king of Jericho, one; the king of Ai, which is beside Bethel, one;',
        10: 'the king of Jerusalem, one; the king of Hebron, one;',
        11: 'the king of Jarmuth, one; the king of Lachish, one;',
        12: 'the king of Eglon, one; the king of Gezer, one;',
        13: 'the king of Debir, one; the king of Geder, one;',
        14: 'the king of Hormah, one; the king of Arad, one;',
        15: 'the king of Libnah, one; the king of Adullam, one;',
        16: 'the king of Makkedah, one; the king of Bethel, one;',
        17: 'the king of Tappuah, one; the king of Hepher, one;',
        18: 'the king of Aphek, one; the king of Lasharon, one;',
        19: 'the king of Madon, one; the king of Hazor, one;',
        20: 'the king of Shimron-meron, one; the king of Achshaph, one;',
        21: 'the king of Taanach, one; the king of Megiddo, one;',
        22: 'the king of Kedesh, one; the king of Jokneam in Carmel, one;',
        23: 'the king of Dor in the heights of Dor, one; the king of Goiim in Gilgal, one;',
        24: 'the king of Tirzah, one: thirty-one kings in all.',
    },
    13: {  # Chapter 13
        1: 'Now Joshua was old and advanced in years, and the LORD said to him, \'You are old and advanced in years, and very much of the land remains to be possessed.\'',
        2: '\'This is the land that remains: all the regions of the Philistines and all the Geshurite territory,\'',
        3: '\'from the Shihor which is east of Egypt, and northward to the border of Ekron — it is counted as Canaanite — the five lords of the Philistines: the Gazite, the Ashdodite, the Ashkelonite, the Gittite, and the Ekronite; and also the Avvim,\'',
        4: '\'from the south, all the land of the Canaanites, and Mearah that belongs to the Sidonians, as far as Aphek, to the border of the Amorites,\'',
        5: '\'and the land of the Gebalites, and all Lebanon toward the east, from Baal-gad below Mount Hermon as far as Lebo-hamath,\'',
        6: '\'all the inhabitants of the hill country from Lebanon as far as Misrephoth-maim, all the Sidonians — I myself will drive them out from before the sons of Israel. Only allot it to Israel as an inheritance, as I have commanded you.\'',
        7: '\'Now therefore divide this land as an inheritance to the nine tribes and the half-tribe of Manasseh.\'',
        8: 'With the other half-tribe, the Reubenites and the Gadites received their inheritance which Moses gave them beyond the Jordan to the east, just as Moses the servant of the LORD gave to them:',
        9: 'from Aroer, which is on the edge of the Valley of the Arnon, and the city that is in the middle of the valley, and all the tableland of Medeba as far as Dibon,',
        10: 'and all the cities of Sihon king of the Amorites, who reigned in Heshbon, as far as the border of the sons of Ammon,',
        11: 'and Gilead, and the territory of the Geshurites and the Maacathites, and all Mount Hermon, and all Bashan as far as Salecah,',
        12: 'all the kingdom of Og in Bashan, who reigned in Ashtaroth and in Edrei — he was the last of the remnant of the Rephaim — for Moses had struck them and dispossessed them.',
        13: 'But the sons of Israel did not dispossess the Geshurites or the Maacathites, and Geshur and Maacath dwell in the midst of Israel to this day.',
        14: 'Only to the tribe of Levi he gave no inheritance; the fire offerings of the LORD, the God of Israel, are their inheritance, as he spoke to them.',
        15: 'And Moses gave an inheritance to the tribe of the sons of Reuben according to their clans.',
        16: 'And their territory was from Aroer, which is on the edge of the Valley of the Arnon, and the city that is in the middle of the valley, and all the tableland by Medeba,',
        17: 'Heshbon and all its cities that are on the tableland: Dibon, and Bamoth-baal, and Beth-baal-meon,',
        18: 'and Jahaz, and Kedemoth, and Mephaath,',
        19: 'and Kiriathaim, and Sibmah, and Zereth-shahar on the hill of the valley,',
        20: 'and Beth-peor, and the slopes of Pisgah, and Beth-jeshimoth,',
        21: 'and all the cities of the tableland, and all the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites who reigned in Heshbon, whom Moses struck down along with the leaders of Midian: Evi, and Rekem, and Zur, and Hur, and Reba — the princes of Sihon who dwelt in the land.',
        22: 'And Balaam the son of Beor, the diviner, the sons of Israel also killed with the sword among the rest of their slain.',
        23: 'And the border of the sons of Reuben was the Jordan and its bank. This was the inheritance of the sons of Reuben according to their clans, the cities and their villages.',
        24: 'And Moses gave an inheritance to the tribe of Gad, to the sons of Gad, according to their clans.',
        25: 'And their territory was Jazer, and all the cities of Gilead, and half the land of the sons of Ammon, as far as Aroer which is east of Rabbah,',
        26: 'and from Heshbon as far as Ramath-mizpeh and Betonim, and from Mahanaim as far as the border of Debir,',
        27: 'and in the valley: Beth-haram, and Beth-nimrah, and Succoth, and Zaphon, the rest of the kingdom of Sihon king of Heshbon, the Jordan and its bank, as far as the lower end of the Sea of Chinnereth, beyond the Jordan to the east.',
        28: 'This is the inheritance of the sons of Gad according to their clans, the cities and their villages.',
        29: 'And Moses gave an inheritance to the half-tribe of Manasseh, and it was for the half-tribe of the sons of Manasseh according to their clans.',
        30: 'And their territory was from Mahanaim, all Bashan, all the kingdom of Og king of Bashan, and all the villages of Jair which are in Bashan — sixty cities,',
        31: 'and half of Gilead, and Ashtaroth, and Edrei, the cities of the kingdom of Og in Bashan — these were for the sons of Machir the son of Manasseh, for half of the sons of Machir according to their clans.',
        32: 'These are the inheritances which Moses distributed in the plains of Moab, beyond the Jordan east of Jericho.',
        33: 'But to the tribe of Levi, Moses gave no inheritance; the LORD, the God of Israel, is their inheritance, as he spoke to them.',
    },
    14: {  # Chapter 14
        1: 'And these are the inheritances which the sons of Israel received in the land of Canaan, which Eleazar the priest, and Joshua the son of Nun, and the heads of the fathers\' houses of the tribes of the sons of Israel distributed to them as inheritance.',
        2: 'By lot was their inheritance, as the LORD had commanded by the hand of Moses, for the nine tribes and the half-tribe.',
        3: 'For Moses had given the inheritance of the two tribes and the half-tribe beyond the Jordan, but to the Levites he gave no inheritance among them.',
        4: 'For the sons of Joseph were two tribes, Manasseh and Ephraim, and they gave no portion to the Levites in the land, except cities to dwell in, with their pasturelands for their livestock and for their possessions.',
        5: 'As the LORD had commanded Moses, so the sons of Israel did, and they divided the land.',
        6: 'Then the sons of Judah drew near to Joshua at Gilgal, and Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite said to him, \'You yourself know the word that the LORD spoke to Moses the man of God concerning me and concerning you at Kadesh-barnea.\'',
        7: '\'I was forty years old when Moses the servant of the LORD sent me from Kadesh-barnea to spy out the land, and I brought back word to him as it was in my heart.\'',
        8: '\'But my brothers who went up with me made the heart of the people melt, yet I wholly followed the LORD my God.\'',
        9: '\'And Moses swore on that day, saying, "Surely the land on which your foot has trodden shall be an inheritance to you and to your sons forever, because you have wholly followed the LORD my God."\'',
        10: '\'And now, behold, the LORD has kept me alive, as he said, these forty-five years since the LORD spoke this word to Moses, while Israel walked in the wilderness. And now, behold, I am this day eighty-five years old.\'',
        11: '\'I am still as strong today as I was on the day Moses sent me; as my strength was then, so my strength is now, for war and for going out and for coming in.\'',
        12: '\'Now therefore give me this hill country of which the LORD spoke on that day, for you yourself heard on that day that the Anakim were there and that the cities were great and fortified. Perhaps the LORD will be with me, and I shall drive them out, as the LORD spoke.\'',
        13: 'And Joshua blessed him, and he gave Hebron to Caleb the son of Jephunneh as an inheritance.',
        14: 'Therefore Hebron became the inheritance of Caleb the son of Jephunneh the Kenizzite to this day, because he wholly followed the LORD, the God of Israel.',
        15: 'Now the name of Hebron was formerly Kiriath-arba — he was the greatest man among the Anakim. And the land had rest from war.',
    },
    15: {  # Chapter 15
        1: 'And the lot for the tribe of the sons of Judah according to their clans reached to the border of Edom, to the wilderness of Zin southward, at the extreme south.',
        2: 'And their southern border was from the end of the Salt Sea, from the bay that faces southward,',
        3: 'and it went out southward of the Ascent of Akrabbim, and passed along to Zin, and went up south of Kadesh-barnea, and passed along by Hezron, and went up to Addar, and turned about to Karka.',
        4: 'And it passed along to Azmon, and went out at the Brook of Egypt, and the border ended at the sea. This shall be your southern border.',
        5: 'And the eastern border was the Salt Sea as far as the mouth of the Jordan. And the border on the northern side was from the bay of the sea at the mouth of the Jordan.',
        6: 'And the border went up to Beth-hoglah, and passed along north of Beth-arabah, and the border went up to the Stone of Bohan the son of Reuben.',
        7: 'And the border went up to Debir from the Valley of Achor, and northward, turning toward Gilgal, which is opposite the Ascent of Adummim, which is south of the valley. And the border passed along to the waters of En-shemesh, and its outlet was at En-rogel.',
        8: 'And the border went up by the Valley of the Son of Hinnom to the southern slope of the Jebusite — that is, Jerusalem. And the border went up to the top of the mountain that is before the Valley of Hinnom on the west, which is at the northern end of the Valley of Rephaim.',
        9: 'And the border extended from the top of the mountain to the spring of the waters of Nephtoah, and went out to the cities of Mount Ephron. Then the border bent around to Baalah — that is, Kiriath-jearim.',
        10: 'And the border turned westward from Baalah to Mount Seir, and passed along to the northern slope of Mount Jearim — that is, Chesalon — and went down to Beth-shemesh, and passed along by Timnah.',
        11: 'And the border went out to the northern slope of Ekron, and the border bent around to Shikkeron, and passed along to Mount Baalah, and went out to Jabneel. And the border ended at the sea.',
        12: 'And the western border was the Great Sea and its coastline. This is the border surrounding the sons of Judah according to their clans.',
        13: 'And to Caleb the son of Jephunneh he gave a portion in the midst of the sons of Judah, according to the command of the LORD to Joshua: Kiriath-arba — Arba being the father of Anak — that is, Hebron.',
        14: 'And Caleb drove out from there the three sons of Anak: Sheshai, and Ahiman, and Talmai, the descendants of Anak.',
        15: 'And he went up from there against the inhabitants of Debir. Now the name of Debir was formerly Kiriath-sepher.',
        16: 'And Caleb said, \'Whoever strikes Kiriath-sepher and captures it, to him I will give Achsah my daughter as wife.\'',
        17: 'And Othniel the son of Kenaz, the brother of Caleb, captured it, and he gave him Achsah his daughter as wife.',
        18: 'And it came about when she came to him, that she urged him to ask her father for a field. And she dismounted from the donkey, and Caleb said to her, \'What do you want?\'',
        19: 'And she said, \'Give me a blessing; since you have given me the land of the Negev, give me also springs of water.\' And he gave her the upper springs and the lower springs.',
        20: 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Judah according to their clans.',
        21: 'And the cities at the farthest part of the tribe of the sons of Judah toward the border of Edom in the Negev were: Kabzeel, and Eder, and Jagur,',
        22: 'and Kinah, and Dimonah, and Adadah,',
        23: 'and Kedesh, and Hazor, and Ithnan,',
        24: 'Ziph, and Telem, and Bealoth,',
        25: 'and Hazor-hadattah, and Kerioth-hezron — that is, Hazor —',
        26: 'Amam, and Shema, and Moladah,',
        27: 'and Hazar-gaddah, and Heshmon, and Beth-pelet,',
        28: 'and Hazar-shual, and Beer-sheba, and Biziothiah,',
        29: 'Baalah, and Iim, and Ezem,',
        30: 'and Eltolad, and Chesil, and Hormah,',
        31: 'and Ziklag, and Madmannah, and Sansannah,',
        32: 'and Lebaoth, and Shilhim, and Ain, and Rimmon — twenty-nine cities in all, with their villages.',
        33: 'In the Shephelah: Eshtaol, and Zorah, and Ashnah,',
        34: 'and Zanoah, and En-gannim, Tappuah, and Enam,',
        35: 'Jarmuth, and Adullam, Socoh, and Azekah,',
        36: 'and Shaaraim, and Adithaim, and Gederah, and Gederothaim — fourteen cities with their villages.',
        37: 'Zenan, and Hadashah, and Migdal-gad,',
        38: 'and Dilean, and Mizpeh, and Joktheel,',
        39: 'Lachish, and Bozkath, and Eglon,',
        40: 'and Cabbon, and Lahmam, and Chitlish,',
        41: 'and Gederoth, Beth-dagon, and Naamah, and Makkedah — sixteen cities with their villages.',
        42: 'Libnah, and Ether, and Ashan,',
        43: 'and Iphtah, and Ashnah, and Nezib,',
        44: 'and Keilah, and Achzib, and Mareshah — nine cities with their villages.',
        45: 'Ekron, with its towns and its villages.',
        46: 'From Ekron and westward, all that were by the side of Ashdod, with their villages.',
        47: 'Ashdod, its towns and its villages; Gaza, its towns and its villages; as far as the Brook of Egypt, and the Great Sea with its coastline.',
        48: 'And in the hill country: Shamir, and Jattir, and Socoh,',
        49: 'and Dannah, and Kiriath-sannah — that is, Debir —',
        50: 'and Anab, and Eshtemoh, and Anim,',
        51: 'and Goshen, and Holon, and Giloh — eleven cities with their villages.',
        52: 'Arab, and Dumah, and Eshan,',
        53: 'and Janim, and Beth-tappuah, and Aphekah,',
        54: 'and Humtah, and Kiriath-arba — that is, Hebron — and Zior — nine cities with their villages.',
        55: 'Maon, Carmel, and Ziph, and Juttah,',
        56: 'and Jezreel, and Jokdeam, and Zanoah,',
        57: 'Kain, Gibeah, and Timnah — ten cities with their villages.',
        58: 'Halhul, Beth-zur, and Gedor,',
        59: 'and Maarath, and Beth-anoth, and Eltekon — six cities with their villages.',
        60: 'Kiriath-baal — that is, Kiriath-jearim — and Rabbah — two cities with their villages.',
        61: 'In the wilderness: Beth-arabah, Middin, and Secacah,',
        62: 'and Nibshan, and the City of Salt, and En-gedi — six cities with their villages.',
        63: 'But as for the Jebusites, the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the sons of Judah could not drive them out, and the Jebusites dwell with the sons of Judah in Jerusalem to this day.',
    },
    16: {  # Chapter 16
        1: 'And the lot went out for the sons of Joseph from the Jordan by Jericho, at the waters of Jericho on the east, going up from Jericho into the hill country, into the wilderness, to Bethel.',
        2: 'And it went out from Bethel to Luz, and passed along to the border of the Archites at Ataroth,',
        3: 'and it went down westward to the border of the Japhletites, as far as the border of Lower Beth-horon, and as far as Gezer, and its outlet was at the sea.',
        4: 'So the sons of Joseph — Manasseh and Ephraim — received their inheritance.',
        5: 'And the border of the sons of Ephraim according to their clans was as follows: the border of their inheritance on the east was Ataroth-addar, as far as Upper Beth-horon.',
        6: 'And the border went out westward at Michmethath on the north, and the border turned about eastward to Taanath-shiloh, and passed along it on the east to Janoah.',
        7: 'And it went down from Janoah to Ataroth and to Naarah, and reached to Jericho, and went out at the Jordan.',
        8: 'From Tappuah the border went westward to the Brook of Kanah, and its outlet was at the sea. This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Ephraim according to their clans,',
        9: 'together with the cities that were set apart for the sons of Ephraim within the inheritance of the sons of Manasseh — all the cities with their villages.',
        10: 'But they did not drive out the Canaanites who dwelt in Gezer, and the Canaanites dwell in the midst of Ephraim to this day and became forced laborers.',
    },
    17: {  # Chapter 17
        1: 'And this was the lot for the tribe of Manasseh, for he was the firstborn of Joseph. As for Machir the firstborn of Manasseh, the father of Gilead, because he was a man of war, he had Gilead and Bashan.',
        2: 'And the lot was for the rest of the sons of Manasseh according to their clans: for the sons of Abiezer, and for the sons of Helek, and for the sons of Asriel, and for the sons of Shechem, and for the sons of Hepher, and for the sons of Shemida. These were the male descendants of Manasseh the son of Joseph, according to their clans.',
        3: 'Now Zelophehad the son of Hepher, the son of Gilead, the son of Machir, the son of Manasseh, had no sons but only daughters, and these are the names of his daughters: Mahlah, and Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, and Tirzah.',
        4: 'And they came near before Eleazar the priest, and before Joshua the son of Nun, and before the leaders, saying, \'The LORD commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers.\' So according to the command of the LORD he gave them an inheritance among the brothers of their father.',
        5: 'And ten portions fell to Manasseh, besides the land of Gilead and Bashan, which is beyond the Jordan,',
        6: 'because the daughters of Manasseh received an inheritance among his sons. And the land of Gilead was for the rest of the sons of Manasseh.',
        7: 'And the border of Manasseh was from Asher to Michmethath, which is east of Shechem. And the border went southward to the inhabitants of En-tappuah.',
        8: 'The land of Tappuah belonged to Manasseh, but Tappuah on the border of Manasseh belonged to the sons of Ephraim.',
        9: 'And the border went down to the Brook of Kanah. These cities, south of the brook, among the cities of Manasseh, belonged to Ephraim. And the border of Manasseh was on the north side of the brook, and its outlet was at the sea.',
        10: 'The land to the south was Ephraim\'s and to the north was Manasseh\'s, and the sea was its border. And on the north they reached to Asher, and on the east to Issachar.',
        11: 'And Manasseh had in Issachar and in Asher: Beth-shean and its towns, and Ibleam and its towns, and the inhabitants of Dor and its towns, and the inhabitants of En-dor and its towns, and the inhabitants of Taanach and its towns, and the inhabitants of Megiddo and its towns — the three of Napheth.',
        12: 'But the sons of Manasseh could not take possession of these cities, and the Canaanites persisted in dwelling in that land.',
        13: 'And it came about when the sons of Israel grew strong, they put the Canaanites to forced labor, but did not utterly drive them out.',
        14: 'And the sons of Joseph spoke to Joshua, saying, \'Why have you given me only one lot and one portion as an inheritance, when I am a numerous people, since the LORD has blessed me until now?\'',
        15: 'And Joshua said to them, \'If you are a numerous people, go up to the forest and clear ground for yourself there in the land of the Perizzites and the Rephaim, since the hill country of Ephraim is too narrow for you.\'',
        16: 'And the sons of Joseph said, \'The hill country is not enough for us, and all the Canaanites who dwell in the land of the valley have chariots of iron, both those in Beth-shean and its towns, and those in the Valley of Jezreel.\'',
        17: 'And Joshua spoke to the house of Joseph — to Ephraim and to Manasseh — saying, \'You are a numerous people and have great power. You shall not have only one lot,\'',
        18: '\'but the hill country shall be yours. Though it is a forest, you shall clear it, and its farthest limits shall be yours. For you shall drive out the Canaanites, though they have chariots of iron, and though they are strong.\'',
    },
    18: {  # Chapter 18
        1: 'And the whole congregation of the sons of Israel assembled at Shiloh and set up the tent of meeting there. And the land was subdued before them.',
        2: 'But there remained among the sons of Israel seven tribes who had not yet divided their inheritance.',
        3: 'And Joshua said to the sons of Israel, \'How long will you be slack about going in to take possession of the land which the LORD, the God of your fathers, has given you?\'',
        4: '\'Appoint for yourselves three men from each tribe, and I will send them out, and they shall arise and walk through the land and describe it according to their inheritance, and then come to me.\'',
        5: '\'And they shall divide it into seven portions. Judah shall stay in his territory on the south, and the house of Joseph shall stay in their territory on the north.\'',
        6: '\'And you shall describe the land in seven portions and bring the description here to me, and I will cast lots for you here before the LORD our God.\'',
        7: '\'For the Levites have no portion among you, for the priesthood of the LORD is their inheritance. And Gad and Reuben and the half-tribe of Manasseh have received their inheritance beyond the Jordan on the east, which Moses the servant of the LORD gave them.\'',
        8: 'And the men arose and went, and Joshua commanded those who went to describe the land, saying, \'Go and walk through the land and describe it, and return to me, and I will cast lots for you here before the LORD at Shiloh.\'',
        9: 'And the men went and passed through the land and described it by cities in seven portions in a book, and they came to Joshua at the camp at Shiloh.',
        10: 'And Joshua cast lots for them at Shiloh before the LORD, and there Joshua divided the land to the sons of Israel according to their divisions.',
        11: 'And the lot of the tribe of the sons of Benjamin came up according to their clans, and the territory of their lot fell between the sons of Judah and the sons of Joseph.',
        12: 'And their border on the north side was from the Jordan, and the border went up to the slope of Jericho on the north, and went up through the hill country westward, and its outlet was at the wilderness of Beth-aven.',
        13: 'And the border passed along from there to Luz, to the southern slope of Luz — that is, Bethel — and the border went down to Ataroth-addar, on the mountain that is south of Lower Beth-horon.',
        14: 'And the border extended from there and turned on the western side southward, from the mountain that is before Beth-horon on the south, and its outlet was at Kiriath-baal — that is, Kiriath-jearim — a city of the sons of Judah. This was the western side.',
        15: 'And the southern side was from the edge of Kiriath-jearim, and the border went out westward, and went out to the spring of the waters of Nephtoah.',
        16: 'And the border went down to the edge of the mountain that is before the Valley of the Son of Hinnom, which is in the Valley of Rephaim on the north, and it went down to the Valley of Hinnom, to the southern slope of the Jebusite, and went down to En-rogel.',
        17: 'And it extended northward and went out to En-shemesh, and went out to Geliloth, which is opposite the Ascent of Adummim, and went down to the Stone of Bohan the son of Reuben.',
        18: 'And it passed along to the north side opposite the Arabah, and went down to the Arabah.',
        19: 'And the border passed along to the north side of Beth-hoglah, and the outlet of the border was at the northern bay of the Salt Sea, at the southern end of the Jordan. This was the southern border.',
        20: 'And the Jordan was its border on the eastern side. This was the inheritance of the sons of Benjamin, by its borders all around, according to their clans.',
        21: 'And the cities of the tribe of the sons of Benjamin according to their clans were: Jericho, and Beth-hoglah, and Emek-keziz,',
        22: 'and Beth-arabah, and Zemaraim, and Bethel,',
        23: 'and Avvim, and Parah, and Ophrah,',
        24: 'and Chephar-ammoni, and Ophni, and Geba — twelve cities with their villages.',
        25: 'Gibeon, and Ramah, and Beeroth,',
        26: 'and Mizpeh, and Chephirah, and Mozah,',
        27: 'and Rekem, and Irpeel, and Taralah,',
        28: 'and Zela, Haeleph, and the Jebusite — that is, Jerusalem — Gibeah, and Kiriath — fourteen cities with their villages. This is the inheritance of the sons of Benjamin according to their clans.',
    },
    19: {  # Chapter 19
        1: 'And the second lot came out for Simeon, for the tribe of the sons of Simeon according to their clans, and their inheritance was in the midst of the inheritance of the sons of Judah.',
        2: 'And they had as their inheritance: Beer-sheba, and Sheba, and Moladah,',
        3: 'and Hazar-shual, and Balah, and Ezem,',
        4: 'and Eltolad, and Bethul, and Hormah,',
        5: 'and Ziklag, and Beth-marcaboth, and Hazar-susah,',
        6: 'and Beth-lebaoth, and Sharuhen — thirteen cities with their villages.',
        7: 'Ain, Rimmon, and Ether, and Ashan — four cities with their villages,',
        8: 'together with all the villages that were around these cities as far as Baalath-beer, Ramah of the Negev. This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Simeon according to their clans.',
        9: 'The inheritance of the sons of Simeon was taken from the portion of the sons of Judah, for the share of the sons of Judah was too large for them, so the sons of Simeon received an inheritance in the midst of their inheritance.',
        10: 'And the third lot came up for the sons of Zebulun according to their clans, and the border of their inheritance reached as far as Sarid.',
        11: 'And their border went up westward and to Maralah, and reached to Dabbesheth, and reached to the brook that is east of Jokneam.',
        12: 'And it turned from Sarid eastward toward the sunrise to the border of Chisloth-tabor, and went out to Daberath, and went up to Japhia.',
        13: 'And from there it passed along eastward to Gath-hepher, to Eth-kazin, and went out to Rimmon, which stretches to Neah.',
        14: 'And the border turned about it on the north to Hannathon, and its outlet was at the Valley of Iphtah-el,',
        15: 'and Kattath, and Nahalal, and Shimron, and Idalah, and Bethlehem — twelve cities with their villages.',
        16: 'This is the inheritance of the sons of Zebulun according to their clans, these cities with their villages.',
        17: 'The fourth lot came out for Issachar, for the sons of Issachar according to their clans.',
        18: 'And their territory was to Jezreel, and Chesulloth, and Shunem,',
        19: 'and Hapharaim, and Shion, and Anaharath,',
        20: 'and Rabbith, and Kishion, and Ebez,',
        21: 'and Remeth, and En-gannim, and En-haddah, and Beth-pazzez.',
        22: 'And the border reached to Tabor, and Shahazumah, and Beth-shemesh, and the outlet of their border was at the Jordan — sixteen cities with their villages.',
        23: 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Issachar according to their clans, the cities with their villages.',
        24: 'And the fifth lot came out for the tribe of the sons of Asher according to their clans.',
        25: 'And their territory was Helkath, and Hali, and Beten, and Achshaph,',
        26: 'and Allammelech, and Amad, and Mishal. And it reached to Carmel on the west and to Shihor-libnath.',
        27: 'And it turned toward the east to Beth-dagon, and reached to Zebulun and to the Valley of Iphtah-el northward to Beth-emek and Neiel, and went out to Cabul on the left,',
        28: 'and Ebron, and Rehob, and Hammon, and Kanah, as far as Great Sidon.',
        29: 'And the border turned to Ramah, and to the fortified city of Tyre, and the border turned to Hosah, and its outlet was at the sea, from the region of Achzib,',
        30: 'and Ummah, and Aphek, and Rehob — twenty-two cities with their villages.',
        31: 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Asher according to their clans, these cities with their villages.',
        32: 'The sixth lot came out for the sons of Naphtali, for the sons of Naphtali according to their clans.',
        33: 'And their border was from Heleph, from the oak in Zaanannim, and Adami-nekeb, and Jabneel, as far as Lakkum, and its outlet was at the Jordan.',
        34: 'And the border turned westward to Aznoth-tabor, and went out from there to Hukkok, and it reached to Zebulun on the south, and to Asher on the west, and to Judah at the Jordan on the east.',
        35: 'And the fortified cities were Ziddim, Zer, and Hammath, Rakkath, and Chinnereth,',
        36: 'and Adamah, and Ramah, and Hazor,',
        37: 'and Kedesh, and Edrei, and En-hazor,',
        38: 'and Iron, and Migdal-el, Horem, and Beth-anath, and Beth-shemesh — nineteen cities with their villages.',
        39: 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Naphtali according to their clans, the cities with their villages.',
        40: 'The seventh lot came out for the tribe of the sons of Dan according to their clans.',
        41: 'And the territory of their inheritance was Zorah, and Eshtaol, and Ir-shemesh,',
        42: 'and Shaalabbin, and Aijalon, and Ithlah,',
        43: 'and Elon, and Timnah, and Ekron,',
        44: 'and Eltekeh, and Gibbethon, and Baalath,',
        45: 'and Jehud, and Bene-berak, and Gath-rimmon,',
        46: 'and Me-jarkon, and Rakkon, with the territory opposite Joppa.',
        47: 'And the territory of the sons of Dan went out beyond them, for the sons of Dan went up and fought against Leshem and captured it and struck it with the edge of the sword and took possession of it and dwelt in it, and they called Leshem, Dan, after the name of Dan their father.',
        48: 'This is the inheritance of the tribe of the sons of Dan according to their clans, these cities with their villages.',
        49: 'When they had finished distributing the land as an inheritance by its borders, the sons of Israel gave an inheritance to Joshua the son of Nun in their midst.',
        50: 'According to the command of the LORD they gave him the city which he asked for: Timnath-serah in the hill country of Ephraim. And he built the city and dwelt in it.',
        51: 'These are the inheritances which Eleazar the priest and Joshua the son of Nun and the heads of the fathers\' houses of the tribes of the sons of Israel distributed by lot at Shiloh before the LORD, at the doorway of the tent of meeting. And they finished dividing the land.',
    },
    20: {  # Chapter 20
        1: 'Then the LORD spoke to Joshua, saying,',
        2: '"Speak to the sons of Israel, saying, \'Designate for yourselves the cities of refuge, of which I spoke to you through Moses,',
        3: 'that the one who kills a person unintentionally, without knowledge, may flee there; and they shall be for you a refuge from the avenger of blood.',
        4: 'And he shall flee to one of these cities and shall stand at the entrance of the gate of the city, and shall speak his words in the ears of the elders of that city; and they shall gather him into the city to themselves and give him a place, and he shall dwell among them.',
        5: 'And if the avenger of blood pursues after him, they shall not hand over the one who killed into his hand, for he struck his neighbor without knowledge, and he did not hate him previously.',
        6: 'And he shall dwell in that city until he stands before the congregation for judgment, until the death of the high priest who is in those days; then the one who killed shall return and come to his own city and to his own house, to the city from which he fled.\'"',
        7: 'So they set apart Kedesh in Galilee in the hill country of Naphtali, and Shechem in the hill country of Ephraim, and Kiriath-arba -- that is, Hebron -- in the hill country of Judah.',
        8: 'And beyond the Jordan, east of Jericho, they designated Bezer in the wilderness on the plateau from the tribe of Reuben, and Ramoth in Gilead from the tribe of Gad, and Golan in Bashan from the tribe of Manasseh.',
        9: 'These were the appointed cities for all the sons of Israel and for the sojourner who sojourns among them, that anyone who kills a person unintentionally may flee there, and not die by the hand of the avenger of blood until he stands before the congregation.',
    },
    21: {  # Chapter 21
        1: 'Then the heads of the fathers\' households of the Levites approached Eleazar the priest, and Joshua the son of Nun, and the heads of the fathers\' households of the tribes of the sons of Israel.',
        2: 'And they spoke to them at Shiloh in the land of Canaan, saying, "The LORD commanded through Moses to give us cities to dwell in, with their pasturelands for our livestock."',
        3: 'So the sons of Israel gave to the Levites from their inheritance, according to the command of the LORD, these cities and their pasturelands.',
        4: 'And the lot came out for the families of the Kohathites; and the sons of Aaron the priest, who were of the Levites, received by lot from the tribe of Judah, and from the tribe of Simeon, and from the tribe of Benjamin, thirteen cities.',
        5: 'And the rest of the sons of Kohath received by lot from the families of the tribe of Ephraim, and from the tribe of Dan, and from the half-tribe of Manasseh, ten cities.',
        6: 'And the sons of Gershon received by lot from the families of the tribe of Issachar, and from the tribe of Asher, and from the tribe of Naphtali, and from the half-tribe of Manasseh in Bashan, thirteen cities.',
        7: 'The sons of Merari according to their families received from the tribe of Reuben, and from the tribe of Gad, and from the tribe of Zebulun, twelve cities.',
        8: 'So the sons of Israel gave these cities and their pasturelands by lot to the Levites, just as the LORD had commanded through Moses.',
        9: 'And they gave from the tribe of the sons of Judah and from the tribe of the sons of Simeon these cities which are mentioned here by name.',
        10: 'And they were for the sons of Aaron, of the families of the Kohathites, of the sons of Levi, for theirs was the first lot.',
        11: 'And they gave them Kiriath-arba -- Arba being the father of Anak -- that is, Hebron, in the hill country of Judah, with its surrounding pasturelands.',
        12: 'But the fields of the city and its villages they gave to Caleb the son of Jephunneh as his possession.',
        13: 'And to the sons of Aaron the priest they gave Hebron, the city of refuge for the one who kills, with its pasturelands, and Libnah with its pasturelands,',
        14: 'and Jattir with its pasturelands, and Eshtemoa with its pasturelands,',
        15: 'and Holon with its pasturelands, and Debir with its pasturelands,',
        16: 'and Ain with its pasturelands, and Juttah with its pasturelands, and Beth-shemesh with its pasturelands -- nine cities from these two tribes.',
        17: 'And from the tribe of Benjamin: Gibeon with its pasturelands, Geba with its pasturelands,',
        18: 'Anathoth with its pasturelands, and Almon with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        19: 'All the cities of the sons of Aaron, the priests, were thirteen cities with their pasturelands.',
        20: 'And the families of the sons of Kohath, the Levites -- the rest of the sons of Kohath -- the cities of their lot were from the tribe of Ephraim.',
        21: 'And they gave them Shechem, the city of refuge for the one who kills, with its pasturelands in the hill country of Ephraim, and Gezer with its pasturelands,',
        22: 'and Kibzaim with its pasturelands, and Beth-horon with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        23: 'And from the tribe of Dan: Eltekeh with its pasturelands, Gibbethon with its pasturelands,',
        24: 'Aijalon with its pasturelands, Gath-rimmon with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        25: 'And from the half-tribe of Manasseh: Taanach with its pasturelands, and Gath-rimmon with its pasturelands -- two cities.',
        26: 'All the cities for the families of the rest of the sons of Kohath were ten, with their pasturelands.',
        27: 'And to the sons of Gershon, of the families of the Levites, from the half-tribe of Manasseh: Golan in Bashan, the city of refuge for the one who kills, with its pasturelands, and Beeshterah with its pasturelands -- two cities.',
        28: 'And from the tribe of Issachar: Kishion with its pasturelands, Daberath with its pasturelands,',
        29: 'Jarmuth with its pasturelands, En-gannim with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        30: 'And from the tribe of Asher: Mishal with its pasturelands, Abdon with its pasturelands,',
        31: 'Helkath with its pasturelands, and Rehob with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        32: 'And from the tribe of Naphtali: Kedesh in Galilee, the city of refuge for the one who kills, with its pasturelands, and Hammoth-dor with its pasturelands, and Kartan with its pasturelands -- three cities.',
        33: 'All the cities of the Gershonites according to their families were thirteen cities with their pasturelands.',
        34: 'And to the families of the sons of Merari, the rest of the Levites, from the tribe of Zebulun: Jokneam with its pasturelands, Kartah with its pasturelands,',
        35: 'Dimnah with its pasturelands, Nahalal with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        36: 'And from the tribe of Reuben: Bezer with its pasturelands, and Jahaz with its pasturelands,',
        37: 'Kedemoth with its pasturelands, and Mephaath with its pasturelands -- four cities.',
        38: 'And from the tribe of Gad: Ramoth in Gilead, the city of refuge for the one who kills, with its pasturelands, and Mahanaim with its pasturelands,',
        39: 'Heshbon with its pasturelands, Jazer with its pasturelands -- four cities in all.',
        40: 'All the cities for the sons of Merari according to their families, the rest of the families of the Levites -- their lot was twelve cities.',
        41: 'All the cities of the Levites in the midst of the possession of the sons of Israel were forty-eight cities with their pasturelands.',
        42: 'Each of these cities had its pasturelands surrounding it; thus it was for all these cities.',
        43: 'So the LORD gave to Israel all the land which He had sworn to give to their fathers, and they possessed it and dwelt in it.',
        44: 'And the LORD gave them rest on every side, according to all that He had sworn to their fathers; and not a man of all their enemies stood before them. The LORD gave all their enemies into their hand.',
        45: 'Not one word of all the good words which the LORD had spoken to the house of Israel failed; all came to pass.',
    },
    22: {  # Chapter 22
        1: 'Then Joshua summoned the Reubenites and the Gadites and the half-tribe of Manasseh,',
        2: 'and said to them, "You have kept all that Moses the servant of the LORD commanded you, and you have listened to my voice in all that I commanded you.',
        3: 'You have not forsaken your brothers these many days, even to this day, but have kept the charge of the commandment of the LORD your God.',
        4: 'And now the LORD your God has given rest to your brothers, just as He spoke to them; so now turn and go to your tents, to the land of your possession, which Moses the servant of the LORD gave to you beyond the Jordan.',
        5: 'Only be very careful to observe the commandment and the law which Moses the servant of the LORD commanded you: to love the LORD your God, and to walk in all His ways, and to keep His commandments, and to cling to Him, and to serve Him with all your heart and with all your soul."',
        6: 'So Joshua blessed them and sent them away, and they went to their tents.',
        7: 'Now to the one half of the tribe of Manasseh Moses had given a possession in Bashan, but to the other half Joshua gave a possession among their brothers beyond the Jordan on the west. And when Joshua sent them away to their tents, he blessed them also,',
        8: 'and spoke to them, saying, "Return to your tents with great wealth, and with very much livestock, with silver and with gold and with bronze and with iron and with very many garments; divide the spoil of your enemies with your brothers."',
        9: 'So the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh returned and departed from the sons of Israel at Shiloh, which is in the land of Canaan, to go to the land of Gilead, to the land of their possession of which they were given possession according to the command of the LORD through Moses.',
        10: 'And they came to the region of the Jordan which is in the land of Canaan, and the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh built there an altar by the Jordan, an altar great in appearance.',
        11: 'And the sons of Israel heard it said, "Behold, the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh have built an altar at the forefront of the land of Canaan, in the region of the Jordan, on the side belonging to the sons of Israel."',
        12: 'And when the sons of Israel heard this, the whole congregation of the sons of Israel assembled at Shiloh to go up against them for war.',
        13: 'Then the sons of Israel sent to the sons of Reuben and to the sons of Gad and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, into the land of Gilead, Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest,',
        14: 'and ten chiefs with him, one chief from each fathers\' house for every tribe of Israel; and each one of them was the head of his fathers\' house among the thousands of Israel.',
        15: 'And they came to the sons of Reuben and to the sons of Gad and to the half-tribe of Manasseh, to the land of Gilead, and they spoke with them, saying,',
        16: '"Thus says the whole congregation of the LORD: \'What is this unfaithfulness that you have committed against the God of Israel, to turn away this day from following the LORD, by building for yourselves an altar, to rebel this day against the LORD?',
        17: 'Is the iniquity of Peor too little for us, from which we have not cleansed ourselves to this day, and there was a plague on the congregation of the LORD,',
        18: 'that you must turn away this day from following the LORD? And it shall be, if you rebel today against the LORD, then tomorrow He will be angry with the whole congregation of Israel.',
        19: 'However, if the land of your possession is unclean, then cross over to the land of the possession of the LORD, where the tabernacle of the LORD stands, and take possession among us; but do not rebel against the LORD, and do not rebel against us, by building for yourselves an altar besides the altar of the LORD our God.',
        20: 'Did not Achan the son of Zerah commit unfaithfulness regarding the devoted things, and wrath fell on all the congregation of Israel? And that man did not perish alone in his iniquity.\'"',
        21: 'Then the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the half-tribe of Manasseh answered and spoke to the heads of the thousands of Israel,',
        22: '"The Mighty One, God, the LORD! The Mighty One, God, the LORD! He knows! And let Israel itself know! If it was in rebellion or in unfaithfulness against the LORD -- do not save us this day! --',
        23: 'if we have built for ourselves an altar to turn away from following the LORD, or if to offer upon it burnt offering or grain offering, or if to make peace offerings upon it, let the LORD Himself require it.',
        24: 'But truly, out of concern for a matter we did this, saying, \'In time to come your sons may say to our sons, "What have you to do with the LORD, the God of Israel?',
        25: 'For the LORD has set the Jordan as a border between us and you, sons of Reuben and sons of Gad; you have no portion in the LORD." So your sons may cause our sons to stop fearing the LORD.\'',
        26: 'Therefore we said, \'Let us now build for ourselves an altar, not for burnt offering and not for sacrifice,',
        27: 'but it shall be a witness between us and you, and between our generations after us, that we are to perform the service of the LORD before Him with our burnt offerings and with our sacrifices and with our peace offerings, so that your sons may not say to our sons in time to come, "You have no portion in the LORD."\'',
        28: 'Therefore we said, \'And it shall be, when they say this to us or to our generations in time to come, then we shall say, "See the copy of the altar of the LORD which our fathers made, not for burnt offering and not for sacrifice, but it is a witness between us and you."\'',
        29: 'Far be it from us that we should rebel against the LORD and turn away this day from following the LORD, by building an altar for burnt offering, for grain offering, or for sacrifice, besides the altar of the LORD our God which stands before His tabernacle."',
        30: 'And when Phinehas the priest and the chiefs of the congregation -- the heads of the thousands of Israel who were with him -- heard the words that the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad and the sons of Manasseh spoke, it was good in their eyes.',
        31: 'And Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest said to the sons of Reuben and to the sons of Gad and to the sons of Manasseh, "Today we know that the LORD is in our midst, because you have not committed this unfaithfulness against the LORD; now you have delivered the sons of Israel from the hand of the LORD."',
        32: 'Then Phinehas the son of Eleazar the priest and the chiefs returned from the sons of Reuben and from the sons of Gad, from the land of Gilead, to the land of Canaan, to the sons of Israel, and brought back word to them.',
        33: 'And the word was good in the eyes of the sons of Israel, and the sons of Israel blessed God and did not speak of going up against them for war, to destroy the land in which the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad were dwelling.',
        34: 'And the sons of Reuben and the sons of Gad called the altar Witness: "For it is a witness between us that the LORD is God."',
    },
    23: {  # Chapter 23
        1: 'And it came to pass after many days, when the LORD had given rest to Israel from all their enemies round about, and Joshua was old, advanced in years,',
        2: 'that Joshua summoned all Israel -- their elders and their heads and their judges and their officers -- and said to them, "I am old, advanced in years.',
        3: 'And you have seen all that the LORD your God has done to all these nations on your account, for the LORD your God is the one who has been fighting for you.',
        4: 'See, I have allotted to you these remaining nations as an inheritance for your tribes, from the Jordan, with all the nations that I have cut off, even to the Great Sea toward the setting of the sun.',
        5: 'And the LORD your God, He shall thrust them out from before you and drive them from before your sight; and you shall possess their land, just as the LORD your God spoke to you.',
        6: 'So be very firm to keep and to do all that is written in the Book of the Law of Moses, so that you do not turn aside from it to the right or to the left,',
        7: 'so that you do not go among these nations, these that remain among you; and you shall not make mention of the name of their gods, nor swear by them, nor serve them, nor bow down to them.',
        8: 'But to the LORD your God you shall cling, just as you have done to this day.',
        9: 'For the LORD has driven out from before you great and mighty nations; and as for you, no man has stood before you to this day.',
        10: 'One man of you puts to flight a thousand, for the LORD your God is the one who fights for you, just as He spoke to you.',
        11: 'So take great heed to yourselves to love the LORD your God.',
        12: 'For if you indeed turn back and cling to the remnant of these nations -- these that remain among you -- and intermarry with them and go among them and they among you,',
        13: 'know with certainty that the LORD your God will no longer drive out these nations from before you; but they shall be a snare and a trap to you, and a whip on your sides and thorns in your eyes, until you perish from off this good land which the LORD your God has given you.',
        14: 'And behold, I am going today the way of all the earth, and you know in all your heart and in all your soul that not one word has failed of all the good words which the LORD your God spoke concerning you; all have come to pass for you -- not one word of them has failed.',
        15: 'And it shall be that just as every good word which the LORD your God spoke to you has come upon you, so the LORD will bring upon you every evil word, until He has destroyed you from off this good land which the LORD your God has given you.',
        16: 'When you transgress the covenant of the LORD your God which He commanded you, and you go and serve other gods and bow down to them, then the anger of the LORD will burn against you, and you will perish quickly from off the good land which He has given you."',
    },
    24: {  # Chapter 24
        1: 'And Joshua gathered all the tribes of Israel to Shechem, and he summoned the elders of Israel and their heads and their judges and their officers, and they presented themselves before God.',
        2: 'And Joshua said to all the people, "Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel: \'Your fathers dwelt beyond the River from ancient times -- Terah, the father of Abraham and the father of Nahor -- and they served other gods.',
        3: 'And I took your father Abraham from beyond the River, and I led him through all the land of Canaan, and I multiplied his seed and gave him Isaac.',
        4: 'And I gave to Isaac, Jacob and Esau; and I gave to Esau Mount Seir to possess it; but Jacob and his sons went down to Egypt.',
        5: 'And I sent Moses and Aaron, and I struck Egypt according to what I did in its midst; and afterward I brought you out.',
        6: 'And I brought your fathers out of Egypt, and you came to the sea; and the Egyptians pursued after your fathers with chariots and horsemen to the Red Sea.',
        7: 'And they cried out to the LORD, and He set darkness between you and the Egyptians, and He brought the sea upon them and covered them; and your eyes saw what I did in Egypt. And you dwelt in the wilderness many days.',
        8: 'And I brought you to the land of the Amorites who dwelt beyond the Jordan, and they fought with you; and I gave them into your hand, and you possessed their land, and I destroyed them from before you.',
        9: 'Then Balak the son of Zippor, king of Moab, arose and fought against Israel; and he sent and called Balaam the son of Beor to curse you.',
        10: 'But I was not willing to listen to Balaam, so he blessed you again and again, and I delivered you from his hand.',
        11: 'And you crossed the Jordan and came to Jericho; and the lords of Jericho fought against you -- the Amorites and the Perizzites and the Canaanites and the Hittites and the Girgashites, the Hivites and the Jebusites -- and I gave them into your hand.',
        12: 'And I sent the hornet before you, and it drove them out from before you -- the two kings of the Amorites -- not by your sword and not by your bow.',
        13: 'And I gave you a land for which you did not labor, and cities which you did not build, and you dwell in them; of vineyards and olive groves which you did not plant, you eat.\'',
        14: '"Now therefore, fear the LORD and serve Him in sincerity and in truth; and put away the gods which your fathers served beyond the River and in Egypt, and serve the LORD.',
        15: 'And if it is evil in your eyes to serve the LORD, choose for yourselves today whom you will serve -- whether the gods which your fathers served that were beyond the River, or the gods of the Amorites in whose land you are dwelling. But as for me and my house, we will serve the LORD."',
        16: 'And the people answered and said, "Far be it from us to forsake the LORD, to serve other gods!',
        17: 'For the LORD our God is the one who brought us and our fathers up from the land of Egypt, from the house of bondage, and who did these great signs before our eyes, and preserved us in all the way in which we walked and among all the peoples through whose midst we passed.',
        18: 'And the LORD drove out from before us all the peoples, even the Amorites dwelling in the land. We also will serve the LORD, for He is our God."',
        19: 'Then Joshua said to the people, "You are not able to serve the LORD, for He is a holy God. He is a jealous God; He will not forgive your transgression or your sins.',
        20: 'If you forsake the LORD and serve foreign gods, then He will turn and do you harm and consume you, after He has done you good."',
        21: 'And the people said to Joshua, "No, but we will serve the LORD!"',
        22: 'Then Joshua said to the people, "You are witnesses against yourselves that you have chosen for yourselves the LORD, to serve Him." And they said, "We are witnesses."',
        23: '"Now therefore, put away the foreign gods which are in your midst, and incline your heart to the LORD, the God of Israel."',
        24: 'And the people said to Joshua, "The LORD our God we will serve, and His voice we will obey."',
        25: 'So Joshua made a covenant with the people that day, and set for them a statute and an ordinance at Shechem.',
        26: 'And Joshua wrote these words in the Book of the Law of God; and he took a great stone and set it up there under the oak that was by the sanctuary of the LORD.',
        27: 'And Joshua said to all the people, "Behold, this stone shall be a witness against us, for it has heard all the words of the LORD which He spoke with us; so it shall be a witness against you, lest you deny your God."',
        28: 'Then Joshua sent the people away, each man to his inheritance.',
        29: 'And it came to pass after these things that Joshua the son of Nun, the servant of the LORD, died, being one hundred and ten years old.',
        30: 'And they buried him in the territory of his inheritance, in Timnath-serah, which is in the hill country of Ephraim, on the north side of Mount Gaash.',
        31: 'And Israel served the LORD all the days of Joshua and all the days of the elders who survived Joshua, and who had known all the work of the LORD which He had done for Israel.',
        32: 'And the bones of Joseph, which the sons of Israel brought up from Egypt, they buried at Shechem, in the piece of ground which Jacob had bought from the sons of Hamor the father of Shechem for one hundred pieces of silver; and they became an inheritance for the sons of Joseph.',
        33: 'And Eleazar the son of Aaron died, and they buried him in the hill of Phinehas his son, which had been given to him in the hill country of Ephraim.',
    },
}

NOTES_JOSHUA = {
    1: {
        1: 'TRANSITION: The phrase \'after the death of Moses\' links Joshua directly to Deuteronomy 34. The title \'servant of the LORD\' (eved YHWH) is the highest honorific in the OT -- Moses held it; Joshua will only receive it at his death (Josh 24:29). Joshua is called \'assistant\' (mesharet), the word used for priests serving in the tabernacle and for angels ministering before God (Psalm 104:4).',
        2: 'HEBREW: \'Moses My servant is dead\' -- three words in Hebrew (Mosheh avdi met) of devastating finality. \'Now therefore arise\' (ve\'attah qum) shifts immediately from mourning to mission. God does not allow prolonged grief to delay His purposes.',
        3: 'PROPHETIC PERFECT: \'I have given it to you\' (netattivu) -- the past tense for a future event. In Hebrew, this construction indicates an action so certain in God\'s decree that it is spoken of as already accomplished. The land is already theirs in the divine council\'s decision; the conquest simply actualizes what God has determined.',
        4: 'GEOGRAPHY: The boundaries match the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 15:18-21) -- from the wilderness (Negev) and Lebanon in the north, to the Euphrates in the east, to the Great Sea (Mediterranean) in the west. \'The land of the Hittites\' may refer to the Hittite Empire\'s former Syro-Canaanite territories, or to the Hittite populations within Canaan. This is the maximum extent of the promised land, only partially achieved under David and Solomon.',
        5: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: \'I will not fail you or forsake you\' -- quoted in Hebrews 13:5 as a promise to every believer through Christ. What was spoken to one man (Joshua) becomes universal through the greater Joshua (Jesus). The Hebrew verbs raphah (fail/let go) and azav (forsake/abandon) are emphatic negations -- God will absolutely never release His grip or walk away.',
        6: 'HEBREW: \'Be strong and courageous\' (chazaq ve\'emats) -- a military commissioning formula used three times in this chapter (vv. 6, 7, 9). Chazaq means \'to be firm, to strengthen oneself\'; emats means \'to be bold, resolute.\' This is the language of a divine commander deploying his general.',
        7: 'TORAH OBEDIENCE: The shift from military courage to Torah faithfulness is deliberate. Success in the conquest depends not on military genius but on covenant obedience. \'Do not turn from it to the right or to the left\' uses the same language Deuteronomy applies to covenant faithfulness (Deut 5:32; 17:11, 20).',
        8: 'KEY VERSE: \'This book of the law shall not depart from your mouth\' -- the verb hagah (meditate) means \'to murmur, to recite audibly,\' not silent contemplation. Joshua is commanded to constantly speak and rehearse Torah. The word for \'success\' (sakal) means \'to act wisely, to prosper\' -- the same root used for the Suffering Servant in Isaiah 52:13. Compare Psalm 1:1-3, which may be modeled on this verse.',
        9: 'DIVINE PRESENCE: \'The LORD your God is with you wherever you go\' -- the \'Immanuel\' principle. God\'s presence is the foundation of all courage. This is not mere encouragement but a theological declaration: the covenant God who split the sea and spoke from Sinai now accompanies Joshua into battle.',
        13: 'HEBREW: \'Rest\' (menukhah) -- a key theological term. YHWH gives \'rest\' from enemies, which is more than absence of conflict. It is the shalom-condition of security, prosperity, and right relationship with God. Hebrews 4:8-11 argues that the rest Joshua gave was incomplete; the true Sabbath rest remains for God\'s people through Christ.',
        18: 'CONTRAST WITH KADESH-BARNEA: The people\'s response here is the theological antithesis of Numbers 14. Where the first generation rebelled and refused to enter, the second generation pledges absolute loyalty, even imposing the death penalty on disobedience. They echo God\'s own charge back to Joshua: \'Only be strong and courageous.\'',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HEBREW WORDPLAY: Rahab\'s name (rahav) is identical to the Hebrew word for the cosmic chaos monster defeated by YHWH (Isa 51:9; Ps 89:10; Job 26:12). A woman named \'Chaos\' who submits to YHWH and is incorporated into Israel is a narrative enactment of the chaos-to-order motif. The word zonah (prostitute) is the same word the prophets use for spiritual unfaithfulness -- a literal Canaanite zonah proves more faithful than Israel will be.',
        4: 'ETHICAL NOTE: Rahab\'s lie to the king\'s men has generated extensive debate. Some argue she is commended for her faith (Heb 11:31) despite her lie; others argue the lie was justified as a lesser evil to protect innocent life (comparable to the Hebrew midwives in Exodus 1:15-21). The text reports the lie without explicit moral commentary; the commendation is for her faith, not her method.',
        6: 'HISTORICAL DETAIL: Stalks of flax (pishtei ha\'ets) drying on the roof confirms the spring season (flax harvest in March-April), consistent with the Jordan crossing during spring flood (Josh 3:15). This kind of incidental detail suggests proximity to the events described.',
        9: 'PSYCHOLOGICAL WARFARE: \'The terror of you has fallen on us, and all the inhabitants of the land have melted away\' -- the verb masas (to melt) describes total psychological collapse. YHWH\'s reputation has preceded His army. The divine warrior\'s advance campaign has succeeded before a single battle is fought.',
        11: 'KEY CONFESSION: \'The LORD your God, He is God in heaven above and on earth beneath\' -- this is the language of Deuteronomy 4:39, the capstone of Moses\' argument for YHWH\'s incomparability. A Canaanite woman articulates the theology of the Deuteronomic worldview. This is a divine council declaration: YHWH rules both the heavenly realm (where the elohim dwell) and the earthly realm. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Rahab the Gentile outsider who confesses YHWH foreshadows Gentile inclusion in the New Covenant.',
        12: 'HEBREW: Chesed (loyal love, covenant faithfulness) -- the covenant term Rahab uses to bind the spies. She is asking for -- and receiving -- inclusion in YHWH\'s covenant community through an act of chesed.',
        18: 'TYPOLOGY: The \'cord of scarlet thread\' (tikvat chut hashani) parallels the Passover blood on the doorposts (Exod 12:7, 13). The Hebrew word tikvah means both \'cord\' and \'hope.\' Rahab\'s scarlet cord is literally her \'scarlet hope.\' The early church father Clement of Rome (~96 AD) identified the scarlet cord as a type of redemption through Christ\'s blood (1 Clement 12:7-8). Those inside the cord-marked house live; those outside die -- exactly the Passover pattern.',
        21: 'IMMEDIATE OBEDIENCE: \'She tied the scarlet cord in the window\' -- Rahab does not wait until the attack. Her faith produces immediate action (James 2:25). The cord of hope is displayed while the city is still standing.',
        24: 'CONTRAST: Compare this report to Numbers 13:31-33. The first spies said \'We are not able to go up against the people.\' These two say \'Surely the LORD has given all the land into our hands.\' Same evidence, opposite conclusion -- the difference is faith in YHWH\'s promises.',
    },
    3: {
        3: 'THE ARK: The ark of the covenant (aron habrit) is YHWH\'s portable throne -- the visible symbol of His presence and sovereignty. It leads the crossing because YHWH Himself leads His people into the land. The 2,000-cubit distance maintains the graduated holiness that protects the people from the dangerous presence of God enthroned on the ark.',
        5: 'CONSECRATION: \'Consecrate yourselves\' (hitqaddeshu) -- ritual preparation involving washing and abstinence, the same preparation required before the Sinai theophany (Exod 19:10-11). The crossing is not merely a military operation but a sacred event -- a theophany that demands ritual readiness.',
        7: 'AUTHENTICATION: The Jordan crossing authenticates Joshua\'s leadership as the Red Sea authenticated Moses\'. \'Just as I was with Moses, so I will be with you\' -- the same presence, the same power, the same God. This is the transfer of divine authority from one leader to the next.',
        10: 'DIVINE TITLE: \'The living God\' (El Chai) -- this title contrasts YHWH with the dead idols of Canaan and the inactive gods who cannot control nature. YHWH is alive, present, and active. The seven nations listed represent the complete (seven = completeness) dispossession of Canaan.',
        11: 'DIVINE COUNCIL TITLE: \'The Lord of all the earth\' (adon kol ha\'arets) -- this is not merely \'God of Israel\' but the cosmic sovereign over all territories and nations. His authority extends over the Jordan because His authority extends over everything. This title challenges the territorial theology of the ANE, where gods had limited jurisdictions.',
        13: 'WATERS CUT OFF: The Hebrew word ned (heap) is the identical term used for the Red Sea miracle in Exodus 15:8 (\'the floods stood upright as a heap\'). The literary connection is deliberate: what YHWH did at the beginning of the exodus, He now does at the end.',
        15: 'TIMING: \'The Jordan overflows all its banks all the days of harvest\' -- the river is at maximum flood stage from spring snowmelt off Mount Hermon. The miracle occurs at the moment of greatest impossibility, magnifying YHWH\'s power.',
        16: 'GEOGRAPHY: \'Adam, the city that is beside Zarethan\' -- approximately 16 miles upstream. The entire stretch of river below that point drained completely. Whether coincidence or literary design, the city named \'Adam\' evokes the original creation, suggesting the conquest is a new creation act. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Jesus\' baptism in the Jordan (Matt 3:13-17) recalls this crossing -- the new Joshua (Yeshua) enters the water and the Spirit descends.',
        17: 'CREATION ECHO: The priests standing on dry ground (charavah) in the middle of the Jordan while all Israel crosses mirrors Genesis 1:9-10, where God gathered the waters to reveal dry land. YHWH is re-creating -- bringing order out of chaos, making a way through the waters for His people.',
    },
    4: {
        3: 'MEMORIAL: Twelve stones from the exact spot where YHWH\'s throne (the ark) held back the waters. These are contact relics -- stones from the place of miracle, designed to trigger covenant memory in future generations. The Hebrew word zikkaron (memorial) is the same term used for the Passover (Exod 12:14).',
        6: 'CATECHISM: \'When your children ask in time to come\' -- this is the same catechetical pattern as the Passover haggadah (Exod 12:26-27; Deut 6:20-25). Faith is transmitted intergenerationally through questions and answers anchored to physical memorials and sacred meals.',
        9: 'HIDDEN WITNESS: Joshua sets up twelve stones IN the middle of the Jordan -- a submerged memorial, invisible under normal water levels, known only to those who remember the crossing. A testimony beneath the surface of the waters of chaos. \'They are there to this day\' -- an eyewitness note indicating the account was written while the stones were still known.',
        14: 'EXALTATION: \'The LORD exalted Joshua in the sight of all Israel\' -- the Jordan is to Joshua what the Red Sea was to Moses: the authenticating miracle that establishes the leader\'s divine authority. They \'revered him just as they had revered Moses.\' The word for \'revered\' (yare) is the same word used for fearing God.',
        19: 'LITURGICAL CALENDAR: The tenth day of the first month -- exactly four days before Passover (Exod 12:3), the day the Passover lamb was selected. The crossing is timed to the exodus liturgical calendar, connecting the entry into the land with the departure from Egypt.',
        23: 'RED SEA PARALLEL: The narrator explicitly connects the Jordan crossing to the Red Sea -- \'just as the LORD your God had done to the Red Sea.\' Then the narrator switches from \'you\' to \'us\' (\'which He dried up before US until WE had crossed over\'), possibly placing himself among the crossing generation -- an eyewitness touch preserved in the text.',
        24: 'UNIVERSAL SCOPE: \'So that ALL the peoples of the earth may know that the hand of the LORD is mighty\' -- the memorial is not merely for Israel\'s internal memory. It is a declaration to the nations, a witness to the peoples allotted to other spiritual powers (Deut 32:8-9) that YHWH is the supreme power. The dual audience: nations (to know) and Israel (to fear).',
    },
    5: {
        1: 'FULFILLED PROPHECY: Rahab\'s private intelligence report (2:9-11) is now publicly confirmed. The verb masas (melted) is the same word she used. The divine warrior\'s advance campaign has succeeded: His reputation has shattered enemy morale before battle begins. This is the strategic context for the rituals that follow -- the enemy is too demoralized to attack while Israel pauses to circumcise and celebrate Passover.',
        2: 'FLINT KNIVES: The use of flint (tsur) rather than metal reflects ritual conservatism -- preserving the archaic form of a practice that predated metallurgy. Circumcision was the Abrahamic covenant sign (Gen 17:10-14) that the wilderness generation had neglected for forty years.',
        6: 'COMMONLY MISUNDERSTOOD: The forty years of wandering were not merely punishment but a complete generational turnover. The uncircumcised wilderness generation was covenantally incomplete -- they bore neither the covenant sign nor the covenant promise. The new generation must be marked before they can inherit.',
        9: 'HEBREW WORDPLAY: \'I have rolled away\' (galoti) gives the place its name Gilgal (from galal, \'to roll\'). The \'reproach of Egypt\' (cherpat Mitsrayim) likely refers to the shame of the slave identity -- uncircumcised, disobedient, unfaithful. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Colossians 2:11-12 speaks of a spiritual circumcision in Christ -- believers have the \'reproach\' of sin rolled away, a new identity conferred through baptism.',
        10: 'BOOKEND PASSOVER: This is the first Passover in the Promised Land -- the bookend to the first Passover in Egypt (Exod 12). In Egypt, Passover protected Israel from the destroyer; at Gilgal, it celebrates deliverance completed. The meal that night marks the transition from exodus to conquest.',
        12: 'TRANSITION: The manna ceases the day after they eat the land\'s produce. The supernatural provision of the wilderness ends because the natural provision of the land begins. But this too requires faith: the land provides because YHWH gives the rain and the harvest (Deut 11:10-15). Exodus 16:35 specifically prophesied this moment: \'The sons of Israel ate the manna forty years, until they came to the border of the land of Canaan.\'',
        13: 'CHRISTOPHANY DEBATE: The \'man\' with a drawn sword is one of the most debated figures in the OT. The drawn sword (cherev shelufah) indicates a warrior ready for battle -- the same posture as the Angel of the LORD before Balaam (Num 22:23). Joshua\'s question -- \'Are you for us or for our adversaries?\' -- reveals human binary thinking. The answer shatters it.',
        14: 'KEY DIVINE COUNCIL TEXT: \'Commander of the army of the LORD\' (sar tseva YHWH) -- a throne-room title. The tseva YHWH is the heavenly host that stands in YHWH\'s throne room (1 Kings 22:19). This figure leads the angelic army. His answer \'No\' (lo) is theologically critical: the Commander does not serve Israel\'s agenda; Israel serves the Commander\'s agenda. The conquest is YHWH\'s war, not Israel\'s. Joshua\'s prostration (yishtachu -- worship) is accepted without rebuke, unlike Revelation 19:10 where the angel refuses worship. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Patristic interpreters (Eusebius, Origen, Theodoret) widely identified this figure as a pre-incarnate appearance of Christ. Hebrews 2:10 calls Jesus the \'pioneer (archegos) of salvation\' -- the NT equivalent of the sar tseva YHWH. See also Revelation 19:11-16, where Christ leads the armies of heaven with a sword.',
        15: 'BURNING BUSH PARALLEL: \'Remove your sandals from your feet, for the place where you are standing is holy\' -- the exact words of Exodus 3:5, where YHWH Himself appeared to Moses in the burning bush. The ground is holy because the divine presence makes it holy. The chapter ends abruptly after Joshua obeys -- the narrative continues seamlessly into the Jericho instructions (chapter 6), suggesting the Commander\'s battle plan IS the Jericho plan. The Commander of heaven\'s army has come to direct the conquest personally.',
    },
    6: {
        1: 'SIEGE CONTEXT: \'Tightly shut up\' (sogeret umesugeret) -- an emphatic double expression meaning completely sealed. The residents have heard of the Jordan miracle and are paralyzed with terror (cf. 2:9-11; 5:1). Jericho is already psychologically defeated before the first circuit.',
        2: 'PROPHETIC PERFECT: \'I have given Jericho into your hand\' (natatti) -- again the past tense for a future event. The outcome is decided in the divine council before the first trumpet sounds. Joshua\'s job is obedience, not strategy.',
        4: 'SEVEN SYMBOLISM: Seven priests, seven trumpets, seven days, seven circuits on the seventh day. The number seven (sheva) saturates the narrative with divine completion. Creation was completed in seven days; Jericho is un-created in seven days. The rams\' horns (yovel) connect to the Jubilee (yovel) -- the year of release and restoration (Lev 25). ESCHATOLOGY: Revelation 8:2, 6 echoes this pattern with seven angels and seven trumpets bringing divine judgment.',
        5: 'HEBREW: The wall shall fall \'flat\' (tachteyha) -- literally \'underneath itself\' or \'in its place.\' The wall collapses vertically, creating a ramp of rubble that soldiers can climb straight up. The war cry (teru\'ah) is the battle cry of the divine warrior and his army (Ps 47:5; Zeph 3:17).',
        10: 'DISCIPLINE OF SILENCE: The commanded silence for six days intensifies the psychological impact. An entire nation marching in disciplined silence around a terrified city, with only the haunting sound of seven rams\' horns breaking the stillness. The silence is not tactical but liturgical -- it builds toward the teru\'ah that will release divine power.',
        17: 'HEREM: \'Under the ban\' (cherem) -- devoted to YHWH for destruction. Everything that breathes is killed; only metals go to YHWH\'s treasury. The herem transforms the city into a sacred offering. COMMONLY MISUNDERSTOOD: The herem is not genocide motivated by ethnic hatred. It is a specific divine command for a specific situation, presented as an act of divine judgment (cf. Gen 15:16, where God delays judgment on the Amorites for 400 years). The herem is never generalized as a model for subsequent warfare.',
        18: 'ACHAN FORESHADOWING: The warning against taking \'things under the ban\' directly anticipates Achan\'s sin in chapter 7. The Hebrew verb chamad (covet) is the same verb used in the tenth commandment (Exod 20:17). The corporate consequence -- \'make the camp of Israel accursed\' -- establishes that one person\'s violation contaminates the entire covenant community.',
        20: 'LITURGICAL WARFARE: The walls fall by divine power, not human engineering. No battering rams, no siege ramps, no undermining. This is cosmic warfare conducted through worship. The ark -- YHWH\'s throne -- is the true siege weapon. 2 Corinthians 10:4: \'The weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh but have divine power to destroy strongholds\' -- the spiritual warfare principle exemplified at Jericho.',
        22: 'COVENANT FAITHFULNESS: Joshua remembers the oath to Rahab. The spies\' covenant promise is honored. YHWH\'s people keep their word, even to a Canaanite prostitute. This models the faithfulness (chesed) that defines covenant relationship.',
        25: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Rahab the Canaanite prostitute is spared and \'has lived in the midst of Israel to this day.\' Matthew 1:5 places her in the genealogy of Jesus: \'Salmon the father of Boaz by Rahab.\' A Gentile woman of disreputable profession is grafted into the covenant people and becomes an ancestor of the Messiah. Hebrews 11:31 celebrates her faith; James 2:25 celebrates her works. She is the OT\'s most powerful picture of grace: salvation by faith alone, from outside the covenant, incorporated into the people of God.',
        26: 'FULFILLED CURSE: Joshua\'s curse on Jericho\'s rebuilder is fulfilled in 1 Kings 16:34: \'In his days Hiel of Bethel built Jericho. He laid its foundation at the cost of Abiram his firstborn, and set up its gates at the cost of his youngest son Segub, according to the word of the LORD, which He spoke by Joshua the son of Nun.\' The curse treats Jericho as permanently devoted territory -- rebuilding it is sacrilege.',
        27: 'SUMMARY: \'So the LORD was with Joshua\' -- the fulfillment of the promise in 1:5. The chapter that began with a sealed, terrified city ends with Joshua\'s fame spreading across the land. But the reader knows where the power comes from: YHWH the divine warrior, who brought down the walls through a worship procession, not a military assault.',
    },
    7: {
        1: 'The Hebrew word \'cherem\' (ban/devoted thing) means everything in Jericho was devoted to the LORD for destruction. Achan\'s theft was stealing from God Himself. The corporate language is critical: \'the sons of Israel acted unfaithfully\' — one man\'s sin contaminated the whole community. This reflects the covenantal solidarity of Israel: the nation stands or falls as one body before God.',
        5: 'Shebarim means \'the broken places\' or \'the quarries.\' The contrast is devastating — at Jericho, walls fell before Israel; now Israel flees and is \'broken.\' Thirty-six deaths may seem small, but it is the first Israelite combat loss in Canaan, shattering the aura of invincibility that Jericho had established.',
        6: 'Joshua\'s response — tearing garments, falling prostrate, dust on the head — mirrors ancient Near Eastern mourning rituals. Falling before the ark is significant: the ark represents the throne of God between the cherubim. Joshua appeals directly to the divine King.',
        7: 'Joshua\'s complaint echoes the wilderness grumbling of the Exodus generation (cf. Exodus 14:11-12, Numbers 14:2-3). The irony is intentional — the same faithless words spoken at the Red Sea now emerge from the mouth of Moses\' successor. God\'s response in v.10 is a sharp rebuke.',
        9: 'Joshua\'s appeal to God\'s \'great name\' echoes Moses\' intercession in Numbers 14:13-16 and Exodus 32:12. The argument is: \'Your reputation among the nations is tied to Israel\'s survival.\' This is not manipulation — it is covenantal logic. God\'s name (shem) is His revealed character and commitment.',
        11: 'The five-fold indictment — sinned, transgressed, taken, stolen, deceived — uses escalating Hebrew verbs. Each \'and also\' (ve-gam) adds another charge. The structure emphasizes that covenant breaking is never a single act but a chain of moral failures.',
        14: 'The lot-casting process (tribes -> clans -> households -> individuals) uses the Hebrew \'lakad\' (to be captured/seized). God\'s sovereign selection narrows from tribe to individual — there is no hiding from the God who sees. This same process appears in 1 Samuel 10:20-21 (selection of Saul) and Jonah 1:7.',
        19: '\'Give glory to the LORD\' (ten kavod la-YHWH) is a solemn call to confess truthfully. The same phrase appears in John 9:24 when the Pharisees interrogate the man born blind. It is a juridical formula: \'speak the truth before God as witness.\'',
        21: 'The \'beautiful mantle from Shinar\' (aderet Shin\'ar) links back to Babylon/Babel (Genesis 10:10, 11:2). Shinar is where human rebellion against God was organized. Achan\'s coveting of Babylonian wealth is symbolically a reaching back toward the old pagan world that Israel was called to leave behind. The Hebrew \'chamad\' (coveted) is the same verb used in the Tenth Commandment (Exodus 20:17) and in Genesis 3:6 when Eve \'saw that the tree was desirable.\'',
        24: 'The Valley of Achor means \'Valley of Trouble.\' Hosea 2:15 later promises that God will make the Valley of Achor \'a door of hope\' — a stunning reversal where the place of judgment becomes a place of restoration. This is prophetic typology: the place of covenant failure becomes the site of covenant renewal.',
        25: 'The punishment of Achan\'s entire household raises a difficult question. Deuteronomy 24:16 says children shall not be put to death for their fathers\' sins. The likely explanation is that Achan\'s family was complicit — the stolen goods were hidden \'inside my tent\' where the family lived. They knew and concealed the theft.',
        26: 'The turning of God\'s anger (the Hebrew \'shuv\' — to turn, return) is a key theological moment. Sin brings divine wrath; dealing with sin restores relationship. The \'great heap of stones\' serves as a permanent memorial, a witness-marker in the landscape.',
    },
    8: {
        1: '\'Do not fear and do not be dismayed\' — this is the covenant warrior formula repeated throughout Joshua (1:9, 8:1, 10:8, 10:25, 11:6). After Achan\'s sin is dealt with, God restores the promise. Notice the key difference from chapter 7: this time God commands \'all the people of war\' — no more half-measures based on human assessment.',
        2: 'The spoil of Ai is permitted for Israel — unlike Jericho. Jericho was the \'firstfruits\' of the conquest, wholly devoted to God (like the firstborn belongs to God). Ai represents the ongoing harvest where God shares the bounty with His people. Achan\'s tragedy is that he took from the firstfruits what God would have freely given from the later harvest.',
        18: 'Joshua stretching out his javelin (kidon) toward Ai is a deliberate parallel to Moses stretching out his staff over the Red Sea (Exodus 14:16) and holding up his hands during the battle with Amalek (Exodus 17:11-12). The extended weapon is a prophetic sign-act: God\'s power flows through the obedient gesture of His appointed leader.',
        26: 'Joshua \'did not draw back his hand\' parallels Moses at Amalek, whose hands were held up by Aaron and Hur (Exodus 17:12). As long as the leader\'s hand is extended in obedience, God gives victory. This is a picture of persistent faith — not magic ritual.',
        29: 'Hanging on a tree and taking the body down before sunset fulfills Deuteronomy 21:22-23: \'his body shall not remain overnight on the tree... for he who is hanged is cursed of God.\' Paul quotes this in Galatians 3:13 regarding Christ: \'Cursed is everyone who hangs on a tree.\' The defeated king of Ai endures the covenant curse; Christ later bears that same curse on behalf of His people.',
        30: 'The altar on Mount Ebal — the mountain of curses, not Gerizim the mountain of blessings — is theologically profound. God meets His people at the place of the curse. The altar of sacrifice stands where the consequences of disobedience are declared. This foreshadows the cross: God\'s grace is displayed precisely at the location of judgment.',
        31: '\'Uncut stones on which no man has wielded an iron tool\' — God\'s altar must not bear the mark of human craftsmanship (Exodus 20:25). Worship is God\'s provision, not human achievement. The altar represents God coming down to meet man, not man building his way up.',
        32: 'Writing the law on stones echoes Deuteronomy 27:2-8. This public display of the Torah at Shechem (between Ebal and Gerizim) establishes the covenant in the heart of the newly conquered land. The law is not hidden — it is carved in public view for all to read.',
        33: 'The ceremony between Ebal and Gerizim fulfills Deuteronomy 11:29 and 27:11-13. The entire nation — including sojourners (gerim) — stands as covenant witnesses. The inclusion of sojourners shows that the covenant community was never purely ethnic. Those who joined Israel shared in both the blessings and obligations.',
        35: '\'Women and the little ones and the sojourners\' — the entire community hears the law read aloud. Biblical covenant is not for an elite priestly class; it is for every member of the community, including those on the social margins.',
    },
    9: {
        3: 'The Gibeonites are identified as Hivites (v.7). Hivites are listed among the nations to be driven out (Deuteronomy 7:1). The Gibeonites\' response to Israel\'s God is a mixture of genuine fear and calculated deception — they acknowledged God\'s power but used lies to secure their survival.',
        14: 'This is the pivotal verse: \'they did not ask for the counsel of the LORD\' (ve-et pi YHWH lo sha\'alu). The Hebrew literally reads \'they did not ask the mouth of the LORD.\' Israel relied on their own senses (examining the moldy bread and worn-out wineskins) rather than seeking divine guidance. This is a recurring pattern in Scripture: human assessment without divine counsel leads to entanglement.',
        15: 'The covenant with the Gibeonites is binding even though obtained through deception, because it was sworn \'by the LORD.\' God holds Israel to oaths made in His name. Centuries later, Saul\'s violation of this covenant brings a three-year famine upon Israel (2 Samuel 21:1-9). God takes covenant fidelity seriously, even when the covenant was made under false pretenses.',
        21: '\'Cutters of wood and drawers of water\' — this is servant labor, but it also placed the Gibeonites in permanent proximity to God\'s altar (v.27). What appears to be a curse becomes a form of inclusion. The Gibeonites lived among God\'s people and served in His sanctuary. The Nethinim (temple servants) mentioned in Ezra and Nehemiah may be descendants of these Gibeonites.',
        23: 'Joshua\'s curse places the Gibeonites in service \'for the house of my God.\' This is significant — their deception led not to destruction but to perpetual service in God\'s presence. In the economy of grace, even those who come to God through imperfect means can find a place in His household.',
        27: '\'In the place which He would choose\' anticipates Deuteronomy\'s theology of the chosen place (Deuteronomy 12:5, 11, 14), which ultimately becomes Jerusalem. The Gibeonites\' service extends from the tabernacle to the temple.',
    },
    10: {
        1: 'Adoni-zedek means \'my lord is righteousness\' — strikingly similar to Melchizedek (\'king of righteousness\'), the priest-king of Salem (Jerusalem) in Genesis 14:18. The contrast is sharp: Melchizedek blessed Abraham and served the Most High God; Adoni-zedek opposes God\'s people. The same city, once a site of blessing, has become a stronghold of resistance to God\'s purposes.',
        8: '\'I have given them into your hand\' — the perfect tense in Hebrew expresses completed action. God speaks of the victory as already accomplished before the battle begins. Faith operates in the gap between God\'s declared word and its visible fulfillment.',
        11: 'The \'great stones from heaven\' (avanim gedolot min ha-shamayim) are hailstones, but the text emphasizes their divine origin — \'from heaven.\' Creation itself fights for Israel. This echoes the cosmic warfare theme: when the LORD of hosts goes to battle, heaven and earth serve as His weapons (cf. Judges 5:20, \'the stars fought from their courses\').',
        12: 'The sun standing still — the Hebrew \'damam\' means \'to be silent, to cease, to stand still.\' Joshua does not pray quietly; he commands the cosmos \'in the sight of Israel.\' This is the LORD of hosts (armies) fighting for Israel. The sun and moon — worshipped as deities throughout the ancient Near East — are shown to be servants of Israel\'s God, obedient to the voice of a man who speaks with divine authority. Some scholars interpret this as a poetic way of describing the battle lasting through the day; others take it as a literal cosmic miracle. Either way, the theological point is clear: God commands creation for the sake of His people.',
        13: 'The Book of Jasher (Sefer HaYashar, \'Book of the Upright\') is referenced as a historical source. It is also cited in 2 Samuel 1:18 (David\'s lament for Saul and Jonathan). This is one of the \'lost books\' — extra-biblical texts cited by Scripture itself. Its existence demonstrates that the biblical authors drew on a broader literary tradition and expected their audience to recognize these sources. The citation formula \'Is this not written in...\' implies readers could verify the account.',
        14: '\'There was no day like that before it or after it\' — a unique event in all history. The text emphasizes not the cosmic miracle itself but its cause: \'the LORD listened to the voice of a man.\' The wonder is not merely that the sun stopped, but that God responded to human speech with cosmic action. This reveals the extraordinary privilege of the covenant relationship.',
        24: '\'Put your feet on the necks of these kings\' — this is ancient Near Eastern victory symbolism, depicted in Egyptian and Assyrian art. It represents total subjugation. Joshua uses it as a teaching moment (v.25): \'thus the LORD will do to all your enemies.\' The physical act becomes a prophetic sign for future battles. Paul echoes this in Romans 16:20: \'The God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet.\'',
        40: 'The summary of the southern campaign uses the phrase \'every breathing thing\' (kol neshamah). The Hebrew \'neshamah\' is the same word used in Genesis 2:7 for the \'breath of life\' God breathed into Adam. The language of creation is inverted: what God breathed into life, the cherem (ban of destruction) now takes. This is the gravity of divine judgment against the Canaanite nations.',
        42: '\'The LORD, the God of Israel, fought for Israel\' — this summary statement is the theological key to the entire southern campaign. Joshua is the human commander, but the LORD is the divine warrior. The holy war is God\'s war; Israel participates in what God initiates and accomplishes.',
    },
    11: {
        1: 'Hazor was the largest and most powerful Canaanite city-state, covering approximately 200 acres — massive by Bronze Age standards. Archaeological excavations confirm a destruction layer dating to the Late Bronze Age. Jabin appears to be a dynastic title (cf. Judges 4:2), as a later \'Jabin king of Hazor\' oppresses Israel in the period of the Judges.',
        4: '\'As many people as the sand on the seashore\' — the same simile used for the covenant promise to Abraham (Genesis 22:17). The enemies of God\'s people are described in language that echoes God\'s promise. The irony is pointed: what God promised Abraham in blessing, the northern coalition marshals in opposition — and still cannot prevail.',
        6: '\'Hamstring their horses and burn their chariots\' — God commands the destruction of military technology rather than its appropriation. Israel must not trust in chariots and horses (Psalm 20:7, Isaiah 31:1). Dependence on superior weapons would replace dependence on God. This command keeps Israel militarily \'primitive\' by design, ensuring their victories can only be attributed to divine power.',
        13: '\'Cities that stood on their mounds\' (tells) — only Hazor was burned. The other cities were left intact for Israel to inhabit, fulfilling Deuteronomy 6:10-11: \'cities which you did not build, houses full of good things which you did not fill.\' God\'s judgment on the nations becomes provision for His people.',
        15: 'The chain of obedience — LORD commanded Moses, Moses commanded Joshua, Joshua did — emphasizes faithful transmission of God\'s word across generations. \'He left nothing undone\' is the highest praise for a leader: complete obedience. Joshua is the model of the faithful servant who executes everything his master commanded.',
        20: '\'It was of the LORD to harden their hearts\' — the same theological pattern as Pharaoh\'s hardening in Exodus. God\'s hardening is not arbitrary; it comes upon those who have already set themselves against His purposes. The Canaanites had centuries of warning (cf. Genesis 15:16, \'the iniquity of the Amorite is not yet complete\'). The hardening serves God\'s purposes of judgment: \'that they might receive no mercy.\' This is the most theologically difficult verse in the conquest narrative.',
        21: 'The Anakim — descendants of Anak, one of the Nephilim-associated giant clans — were the very people whose size terrified the spies in Numbers 13:33 (\'we were like grasshoppers in our own sight\'). Joshua completes what the previous generation refused to attempt. The giants who caused Israel to falter at Kadesh-barnea are now destroyed by the faithful generation.',
        22: '\'Only in Gaza, in Gath, and in Ashdod some remained\' — these are Philistine cities. Goliath of Gath (1 Samuel 17) was likely a descendant of these surviving Anakim. The remnant of the giants in Philistine territory sets up the David and Goliath narrative generations later. What Joshua left unfinished, David would complete with a sling and a stone.',
        23: '\'The land had rest from war\' (ve-ha\'arets shaqetah mil-milchamah) — this is the Sabbath-rest theme. The conquest, like creation, ends with rest. The Hebrew \'shaqat\' (to be quiet, at rest) anticipates the \'rest\' theology developed in Hebrews 3-4, where the author argues that Joshua\'s rest was not the ultimate fulfillment — that remains in Christ (Hebrews 4:8-9, \'if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day\').',
    },
    12: {
        1: 'Chapter 12 functions as a victory ledger — the formal record of conquered kings. Ancient Near Eastern kings kept conquest lists on temple walls and royal inscriptions. This chapter serves the same function but attributes every victory to the LORD. The two sections are: Transjordan conquests under Moses (vv.1-6) and Cisjordan conquests under Joshua (vv.7-24).',
        4: 'Og king of Bashan is called \'one of the remnant of the Rephaim.\' The Rephaim were the giant clans of the ancient world (cf. Deuteronomy 2:10-11, 3:11 where Og\'s iron bed is described as thirteen feet long). The conquest of Og under Moses and the Anakim under Joshua together demonstrate that God\'s people overcome the most terrifying physical opponents when God fights for them.',
        6: 'Moses\' conquests in Transjordan (Numbers 21, Deuteronomy 2-3) are included in Joshua\'s victory list because the conquest is one continuous divine campaign. Moses began what Joshua completed. The land given to Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh is part of the same inheritance.',
        24: 'Thirty-one kings — the number represents the comprehensive defeat of Canaan\'s royal power structure. Each \'one\' (echad) after each king\'s name has a cumulative rhetorical effect in the Hebrew: king after king after king, all fallen. The entire political and military infrastructure of Canaan has been dismantled. The repetitive \'one... one... one\' reads like the tolling of a bell — a liturgy of divine judgment. Christ typology: as Joshua conquered thirty-one earthly kings, Christ conquered principalities and powers (Colossians 2:15), making a public spectacle of them.',
    },
    13: {
        1: 'The LORD\'s statement to aging Joshua is striking in its candor. The Hebrew zaqanta ba\'ta bayyamim (\'you are old, advanced in days\') is the same phrase used of Abraham (Gen 24:1). Much land remains unpossessed -- a theological theme: God grants, but Israel must still walk it out. The tension between divine gift and human responsibility runs through the entire book.',
        3: 'The \'five lords of the Philistines\' (sarnei pelishtim) -- the word seren (lord) is a uniquely Philistine title, possibly cognate with Greek tyrannos. The five cities (Gaza, Ashdod, Ashkelon, Gath, Ekron) formed a pentapolis that would trouble Israel for centuries, culminating in the David-Goliath narrative.',
        5: 'Lebo-hamath (\'entrance of Hamath\') marks the ideal northern boundary of the Promised Land (Num 34:8). Israel never fully possessed to this line except briefly under Solomon (1 Kings 8:65). The gap between promise and possession is a warning.',
        12: 'Og king of Bashan -- \'the last of the remnant of the Rephaim.\' The Rephaim were a race of giants connected to the Nephilim tradition (Gen 6:4, \'also afterward\'). Og\'s territory included 60 fortified cities (Deut 3:4). His iron bedstead measured 9 by 4 cubits (~13.5 x 6 feet, Deut 3:11). The defeat of the Rephaim is a major theme: God systematically dismantles the giant strongholds throughout the conquest.',
        13: 'A sobering note: the Geshurites and Maacathites were never expelled. \'To this day\' indicates the author writing during a period when these peoples still dwelt in Israel. David later married Maacah, daughter of the king of Geshur (2 Sam 3:3), and their son Absalom fled to Geshur after murdering Amnon.',
        14: 'Levi\'s \'inheritance\' is the LORD Himself and His fire offerings (isheh YHWH). This establishes the priestly economic system: no territorial allotment, but sustained by the tithes and offerings of the other tribes. This is picked up in the NT: \'The Lord is my portion\' (Lam 3:24; cf. Ps 16:5, 73:26).',
        22: 'Balaam son of Beor -- the pagan diviner of Numbers 22-24 who blessed Israel but then counseled Moab to seduce Israel through sexual immorality and idolatry (Num 31:16). He is killed here among the Midianite casualties. The NT uses Balaam as a warning type: the \'way of Balaam\' (2 Pet 2:15), \'error of Balaam\' (Jude 11), \'teaching of Balaam\' (Rev 2:14).',
        33: 'Repeated from v.14 with emphasis: \'the LORD, the God of Israel, is their inheritance.\' The shift from \'fire offerings\' (v.14) to \'the LORD Himself\' (v.33) is significant -- the offerings are the means, but God Himself is the substance of Levi\'s portion.',
    },
    14: {
        6: 'Caleb is called \'the Kenizzite\' -- Kenaz was an Edomite clan (Gen 36:11,15). This means Caleb was likely a non-Israelite by blood who was fully incorporated into Judah. His faith, not his ethnicity, defined his standing. This prefigures the inclusion of Gentiles by faith throughout Scripture.',
        7: 'Caleb\'s self-description: \'I brought back word to him as it was in my heart\' -- Hebrew ka\'asher im-levavi. He reported honestly what he saw, neither exaggerating the danger (like the ten spies) nor minimizing it. Faithful report vs. fearful report. Caleb saw the same giants but drew different conclusions.',
        8: '\'My brothers made the heart of the people melt\' -- hemassiu et-lev ha\'am. The same verb (masas, \'melt\') used of the Canaanites\' fear in Josh 2:11. Irony: Israel\'s own spies caused in Israel the very fear that God was putting in the Canaanites.',
        10: '\'The LORD has kept me alive\' -- forty-five years since Kadesh-barnea: 38 years of wilderness wandering + 7 years of conquest campaigns. Caleb is 85 years old. The wilderness was punishment for the faithless generation, but Caleb walked through it sustained by promise.',
        11: '\'As my strength was then, so my strength is now\' -- this is not mere physical boasting. The Hebrew kohi az kohi attah frames strength as something sustained by divine promise. Caleb at 85 claims combat readiness because God\'s word has not yet been fulfilled to him.',
        12: 'Caleb\'s faith confession: \'Give me this hill country\' -- at 85 years old, he asks for the HARDEST territory, where the Anakim giants still live in great fortified cities. This is the opposite of the fear at Kadesh-barnea 45 years earlier. TYPOLOGY: Faith does not ask for the easy path but for the place where God\'s power is most needed. \'Perhaps the LORD will be with me\' -- not doubt but deference (Hebrew ulai, \'if it be that\'). Caleb does not presume, yet he advances.',
        15: 'Kiriath-arba = \'City of Arba,\' and Arba was \'the greatest man among the Anakim.\' ha\'adam haggadol ba\'anaqim -- literally \'the great man among the Anakim.\' This is Hebron, where Abraham purchased the cave of Machpelah to bury Sarah (Gen 23). Abraham\'s burial site was a giant stronghold. Caleb reclaims it. \'The land had rest from war\' -- the Hebrew shaqetah min-milchamah is the same phrase used in Judges for periods of peace after deliverance.',
    },
    15: {
        2: 'The Salt Sea (yam hammelach) = the Dead Sea. Judah\'s territory is anchored by this landmark on the east and the Great Sea (Mediterranean) on the west -- the largest tribal allotment, befitting the royal tribe.',
        7: 'The Valley of Achor (\'Trouble\') -- where Achan was executed for taking devoted things (Josh 7). A place of judgment becomes a boundary marker. Hosea later prophesies that the Valley of Achor will become \'a door of hope\' (Hos 2:15).',
        8: 'The Valley of the Son of Hinnom (gei ben-Hinnom) -- later corrupted to \'Gehenna.\' This valley south of Jerusalem became the site of child sacrifice under Ahaz and Manasseh (2 Chr 28:3, 33:6) and was cursed by Jeremiah (Jer 7:31-32, 19:6). By the intertestamental period, it became the standard image for the place of final punishment. Jesus uses \'Gehenna\' as the word for hell (Matt 5:22, 10:28, Mark 9:43).',
        13: 'Caleb receives Kiriath-arba/Hebron \'according to the command of the LORD to Joshua\' -- al pi YHWH. This was not Joshua\'s decision but God\'s direct order. The giant stronghold must fall to the man of faith.',
        14: 'The three sons of Anak: Sheshai, Ahiman, and Talmai. These are the same clans the terrified spies reported in Numbers 13:22. Caleb personally drives them out -- the very giants that paralyzed the previous generation.',
        17: 'Othniel son of Kenaz, Caleb\'s younger brother (or nephew), captures Debir. He becomes the first judge of Israel (Judg 3:9-11). Caleb\'s faith produces a legacy: his family becomes a dynasty of deliverers.',
        19: 'Achsah\'s request for springs of water alongside the Negev land is wisdom, not greed. Negev land without water is worthless. She asks for what makes the gift functional. Caleb gives generously: upper AND lower springs. TYPOLOGY: The believer who receives land (salvation) also needs living water (the Spirit).',
        32: '\'Twenty-nine cities\' -- but counting the names yields more than 29. Ancient scribal practice sometimes counted only primary cities, with dependent towns included under a primary city\'s count. This is a textual feature, not an error.',
        47: 'Judah\'s territory extends to the Philistine coast: Ashdod, Gaza. These were claimed but not fully controlled -- the Philistine pentapolis remained a thorn throughout the Judges period and into the monarchy.',
        63: 'The critical failure verse: \'The Jebusites dwell with the sons of Judah in Jerusalem to this day.\' Judah could not drive out Jerusalem\'s inhabitants. This failure persisted for ~400 years until David conquered the Jebusite fortress (2 Sam 5:6-7) and made it his capital. Partial obedience has generational consequences. The \'to this day\' formula indicates the author wrote before David\'s conquest, placing at least this portion of Joshua in the pre-Davidic period.',
    },
    16: {
        1: 'The \'lot of the sons of Joseph\' -- Joseph received the double portion of the firstborn (through Ephraim and Manasseh), even though Reuben was Jacob\'s biological firstborn. Jacob\'s blessing in Genesis 48 elevated Joseph\'s sons to tribal status.',
        4: '\'Manasseh and Ephraim received their inheritance\' -- note the reversed order from Gen 48. Jacob placed Ephraim first prophetically; here the historical narrative lists Manasseh first as the biological firstborn. Both orderings are preserved in the text.',
        10: 'Second failure verse: Ephraim did not drive out the Canaanites of Gezer. Instead they became forced laborers (mas-oved). Gezer was not fully Israelite until Pharaoh conquered it and gave it as a dowry to Solomon\'s Egyptian wife (1 Kings 9:16). That is ~400 years of compromise.',
    },
    17: {
        3: 'Zelophehad\'s daughters (Mahlah, Noah, Hoglah, Milcah, Tirzah) -- their inheritance case was decided by Moses in Numbers 27:1-11 and confirmed in Numbers 36. Here the promise is fulfilled: they receive land in Manasseh. This is one of the earliest recorded legal precedents for women\'s property rights in the ancient Near East.',
        4: '\'The LORD commanded Moses to give us an inheritance among our brothers\' -- the daughters appeal to divine command, not cultural convention. And Joshua honors it without hesitation. Law and promise override custom.',
        11: 'Beth-shean, Ibleam, Dor, En-dor, Taanach, Megiddo -- these are the great fortress cities controlling the Jezreel Valley and its approaches. Megiddo guarded the pass through the Carmel ridge on the Via Maris, the international highway. \'The three of Napheth\' (shelosheth hannapheth) is obscure -- possibly \'the three heights\' or three district capitals.',
        12: 'Third failure verse in this section: Manasseh could not take these cities. The Canaanite chariot cities in the valleys remained unconquered. Iron chariots dominated flat terrain -- Israel\'s strength was in hill country warfare.',
        15: 'Joshua\'s response to Joseph\'s complaint is masterful leadership: \'If you are numerous, go clear the forest.\' He does not deny their size but redirects their energy from complaint to action. The Rephaim and Perizzites in the forests were real threats, but Joshua says a great people should welcome great challenges.',
        16: '\'Chariots of iron\' (rekev barzel) -- the Canaanite military advantage. Iron technology gave the lowland Canaanites superiority on flat ground. Israel would not master iron-working until the early monarchy period (1 Sam 13:19-22). But God\'s promise overrides technological disadvantage (cf. Josh 11:6-9, Judg 4:15).',
        18: 'Joshua\'s final word to Joseph: \'You SHALL drive out the Canaanites, though they have chariots of iron, and though they are strong.\' This is both command and prophecy. The \'though\' (ki) acknowledges the difficulty while asserting the certainty of victory. Faith does not deny obstacles; it overcomes them.',
    },
    18: {
        1: 'The tabernacle moves to Shiloh -- a pivotal moment. Shiloh in the hill country of Ephraim becomes the central sanctuary for the entire pre-monarchic period (~300 years, until its destruction ~1050 BC, 1 Sam 4). \'The land was subdued before them\' (nikbeshah ha\'aretz) -- the same verb as Gen 1:28 (\'subdue the earth\'). Conquest fulfills the creation mandate.',
        3: 'Joshua rebukes the remaining tribes: \'How long will you be slack?\' (ad-anah attem mitrappim). Seven tribes have not yet possessed their allotments. Promise does not automatically become possession -- active appropriation is required.',
        9: 'The land survey team \'described it by cities in seven portions in a book\' (sepher). This is one of the earliest references to written cadastral (land-survey) documentation in history. The administrative sophistication of the allotment is often underappreciated.',
        12: 'Benjamin\'s territory falls \'between Judah and Joseph\' -- geographically between the two power blocs of the south and north. This strategic position makes Benjamin a buffer and a kingmaker. Saul, Israel\'s first king, was a Benjaminite. Jerusalem sits on Benjamin\'s border with Judah.',
        16: 'The Valley of Rephaim appears again as a boundary marker. This valley southwest of Jerusalem was named for the Rephaim giants. David would later fight the Philistines here twice (2 Sam 5:18-25). The giant-named geography persists even after the giants themselves are gone.',
        28: '\'The Jebusite, that is Jerusalem\' -- listed among Benjamin\'s cities. Jerusalem sat on the border of Benjamin and Judah (cf. 15:8, 15:63). Both tribes claimed it; neither fully held it until David. Kiriath (possibly short for Kiriath-jearim) is also listed -- where the Ark would rest after its return from the Philistines (1 Sam 7:1-2).',
    },
    19: {
        1: 'Simeon\'s inheritance is \'in the midst of Judah\' -- not a separate territory but cities within Judah\'s borders. This fulfills Jacob\'s prophecy: \'I will divide them in Jacob and scatter them in Israel\' (Gen 49:7). Simeon and Levi were cursed for the Shechem massacre (Gen 34). Levi was \'scattered\' as priests; Simeon was absorbed into Judah.',
        9: 'The explicit reason: \'The share of Judah was too large for them.\' Judah\'s allotment was oversized, so Simeon received cities within it. By the time of the monarchy, Simeon is essentially merged with Judah. The tribe nearly disappears from history -- conspicuously absent from Moses\' blessing in Deut 33.',
        10: 'Zebulun\'s allotment in lower Galilee. Jacob prophesied Zebulun would dwell by the shore of the sea (Gen 49:13), and indeed their territory was near both the Sea of Galilee and the Mediterranean trade routes, though not directly coastal.',
        15: 'Bethlehem is listed among Zebulun\'s cities -- NOT the famous Bethlehem in Judah, but Bethlehem of Zebulun (cf. Judg 12:8-10). This is a different town, about 7 miles northwest of Nazareth.',
        22: 'Issachar\'s border \'reached to Tabor\' -- Mount Tabor, the dramatic isolated mountain rising from the Jezreel Valley floor. This is where Deborah and Barak would muster against Sisera (Judg 4:6). Christian tradition identifies it with the Transfiguration (Matt 17:1-8), though this is uncertain.',
        28: '\'As far as Great Sidon\' (Tsidon rabbah) -- Asher\'s territory reached to the Phoenician coast including the approach to Sidon, though they never controlled it (Judg 1:31). The gap between allotment and achievement is a recurring theme.',
        29: '\'The fortified city of Tyre\' (ir mivtsar-Tsor) -- Asher\'s allotment included Tyre, which would become the greatest commercial city of the ancient Mediterranean. Israel never held it. Tyre remained independent Phoenician throughout biblical history.',
        34: '\'To Judah at the Jordan on the east\' -- this is a difficult clause. Some understand it as a reference to a settlement called Judah east of the Jordan; others emend the text. The LXX reads differently. It may refer to Judahite settlements in the Transjordan (cf. the Havvoth-jair tradition).',
        35: '\'Chinnereth\' -- the city that gives its name to the Sea of Chinnereth (= Sea of Galilee). The name may derive from kinnor (\'harp\'), describing the lake\'s shape. This is the lake where Jesus would center much of His ministry.',
        38: 'Naphtali receives 19 fortified cities including Kedesh (a future city of refuge, Josh 20:7) and Beth-shemesh (\'House of the Sun\') and Beth-anath (\'House of Anath\'). The theophoric elements in these names reveal Canaanite sun-worship and Anath-worship that Israel was supposed to eradicate.',
        40: 'Dan receives the seventh and final lot. Their territory is on the coastal plain between Judah and Ephraim -- directly facing the Philistines. This proved untenable.',
        47: 'The pivotal verse for Dan: \'The territory of Dan went out beyond them\' -- Hebrew vayyetse gevul benei-Dan mehem. Unable to hold their coastal allotment against Amorite/Philistine pressure (Judg 1:34), the Danites migrated north and conquered Leshem/Laish (Judg 18), renaming it Dan. This northern Dan (\'from Dan to Beer-sheba\') later became a site of Jeroboam\'s golden calf idolatry (1 Kings 12:29). Dan\'s failure to hold their God-given territory led to idolatry at their self-chosen territory.',
        49: 'After all tribal allotments, Israel gives Joshua his personal inheritance. He chose last, after everyone else received their portion. The leader serves the people first.',
        50: 'Timnath-serah (\'portion of abundance\' or \'portion of the sun\') in the hill country of Ephraim -- Joshua\'s own tribe. In Judges 2:9 it is called Timnath-heres (with reversed letters). \'He built the city and dwelt in it\' -- the conqueror of Canaan builds himself a single city in his own tribe\'s hill country. Compare Moses who received no inheritance at all. The pattern of servant leadership.',
        51: 'The colophon summarizing the entire allotment: Eleazar (priestly authority), Joshua (civil-military authority), and the tribal heads (representative authority) distributed land by lot (divine authority) at Shiloh before the LORD at the tent of meeting. Four layers of authority converge. \'And they finished dividing the land\' -- vayekhullu mechallaq et-ha\'aretz. The verb kala (\'finish/complete\') echoes Genesis 2:1 -- \'the heavens and earth were finished.\' As creation was completed, so the new creation of Israel\'s inheritance is completed.',
    },
    20: {
        2: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The cities of refuge point directly to Christ. The manslayer flees to the city for protection from the avenger of blood (the go\'el haddam) -- just as the sinner flees to Christ for protection from the law\'s death penalty (Rom 6:23). The manslayer must remain in the city until the death of the high priest -- Christ our High Priest died once for all (Heb 7:27), and His death opens permanent refuge. Under the old covenant the death of the high priest released the manslayer; under the new covenant the death of THE High Priest releases all who take refuge in Him. Numbers 35:25-28 provides the foundational legislation that Joshua 20 now implements.',
        3: 'HEBREW: bishgagah, \'in error / unintentionally\' -- the cities of refuge are specifically for unintentional killing, not premeditated murder. Numbers 35:16-21 defines the distinction. The go\'el haddam (avenger of blood) was the nearest male relative obligated to pursue blood justice -- a deeply embedded ANE institution. The cities of refuge tempered blood vengeance with due process.',
        6: 'The manslayer must dwell in the city of refuge until \'the death of the high priest.\' This is one of the most theologically pregnant provisions in the Torah. It binds the release of the guilty to the death of the priestly mediator -- a clear foreshadowing of Christ\'s atoning death. The \'congregation\' (edah) served as the judicial body determining guilt or innocence (Num 35:24-25).',
        7: 'Three cities west of the Jordan: Kedesh (Naphtali, in the north), Shechem (Ephraim, in the center), and Hebron (Judah, in the south). The geographic spread ensured that no Israelite was ever too far from refuge. Kiriath-arba is identified as Hebron -- Arba was the greatest man among the Anakim (Josh 14:15). That the city of the giants becomes a city of mercy is a quiet irony.',
        8: 'Three cities east of the Jordan: Bezer (Reuben), Ramoth in Gilead (Gad), and Golan in Bashan (Manasseh). Six cities total -- three on each side of the Jordan, distributed so that refuge was accessible from any location in the land. Deuteronomy 19:1-13 commanded this arrangement. Moses had already designated the three eastern cities (Deut 4:41-43); Joshua now completes the system.',
        9: 'The cities of refuge were open to the ger (sojourner/alien) as well as to native Israelites. This universality is significant: God\'s provision of refuge was not limited by ethnicity. The principle anticipates the gospel\'s universal offer of salvation -- \'whosoever will may come\' (Rev 22:17). Christ is the refuge for all nations.',
    },
    21: {
        1: 'The Levites approach the leadership -- Eleazar the priest, Joshua, and the tribal heads -- to claim their cities. Unlike the other tribes, Levi received no territorial inheritance (Num 18:20-24; Deut 10:9). Instead, they received 48 cities scattered throughout all twelve tribal territories, with surrounding pasturelands for their livestock.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Every tribe gave cities to the Levites. This ensured that the priestly teaching class was distributed throughout Israel rather than concentrated in one region. The Levites were the LORD\'s portion (Num 18:20), and their scattering fulfilled Jacob\'s prophecy of Genesis 49:7 -- \'I will divide them in Jacob and scatter them in Israel.\' What was pronounced as a curse on Levi for Shechem\'s violence was transformed by God\'s grace into a blessing: the Levites\' scattering became the mechanism for teaching the Torah throughout the entire land (Deut 33:10; 2 Chr 17:7-9).',
        4: 'The three Levitical clans -- Kohath, Gershon, and Merari -- receive their cities by lot. The Kohathites are divided: the sons of Aaron (the priestly line) receive 13 cities from Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin (the southern tribes closest to the future temple site). The remaining Kohathites receive 10 cities from Ephraim, Dan, and half-Manasseh.',
        13: 'Hebron is both a city of refuge (Josh 20:7) and a Levitical city. It served dual functions: sanctuary for the manslayer and residence for the priests. This overlap underscores the priestly role in administering justice and providing sanctuary.',
        41: 'Forty-eight cities total for the Levites -- a number that ensured comprehensive coverage of the entire land. The Levitical city system was essentially an educational and worship infrastructure: Torah teachers in every region, accessible to every Israelite. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: As the Levites were scattered to bring God\'s word to every tribe, so Christ sent His disciples to every nation (Matt 28:19-20). The Levitical system was a foreshadowing of the Great Commission.',
        43: 'FULFILLMENT FORMULA: \'So the LORD gave to Israel all the land which He had sworn to give to their fathers.\' This is the first of three summary statements (vv. 43-45) that form the theological climax of the entire book from chapters 13-21. God\'s promise to Abraham (Gen 12:7; 15:18-21) is declared fulfilled.',
        44: '\'The LORD gave them rest on every side.\' Rest (menukhah) is one of the central theological themes of Joshua. God promised rest (Deut 12:10); God delivered rest. \'Not a man of all their enemies stood before them\' -- total military victory, as promised in Deuteronomy 11:25. The rest that Joshua gave was temporal and incomplete (Heb 4:8); the true and eternal rest comes through Jesus (Heb 4:9-11), whose name is the Greek form of Joshua.',
        45: '\'Not one word of all the good words which the LORD had spoken to the house of Israel failed; all came to pass.\' This is the single most important theological statement in the book of Joshua. God\'s faithfulness is absolute -- 100% fulfillment rate. This verse is echoed in Joshua 23:14 and forms the basis of Joshua\'s farewell argument: because God kept every promise of blessing, He will also keep every warning of judgment. God\'s word never fails.',
    },
    22: {
        1: 'Joshua now formally dismisses the Transjordan tribes (Reuben, Gad, and the half-tribe of Manasseh). They had fulfilled their obligation from Numbers 32: fight alongside their brothers until the land is conquered, then return to their eastern inheritance. Their faithfulness throughout the entire conquest is commended.',
        5: 'Joshua\'s parting charge to the eastern tribes is essentially the Shema in expanded form: \'love the LORD your God, walk in all His ways, keep His commandments, cling to Him, serve Him with all your heart and with all your soul.\' Five covenant verbs -- love, walk, keep, cling, serve -- summarize the entire Torah\'s demand. This is the concentrated essence of Deuteronomy 6:4-5. Jesus identified these same commands as the greatest commandment (Matt 22:37-38).',
        10: 'The eastern tribes build \'an altar great in appearance\' at the Jordan. The Hebrew emphasizes its size -- this was no modest memorial but a structure visible from a distance. The location \'in the land of Canaan\' (on the western bank or in the Jordan region) makes it even more provocative, since it was built in territory belonging to the western tribes.',
        12: 'The western tribes assemble at Shiloh \'to go up against them for war.\' This extreme reaction is theologically grounded: Deuteronomy 13:12-16 commands Israel to destroy any Israelite city that establishes idolatrous worship. The western tribes take covenant faithfulness so seriously that they are prepared to fight their own brothers. Zeal without investigation, however, nearly leads to catastrophe.',
        17: 'The \'iniquity of Peor\' refers to Numbers 25:1-9, when Israel engaged in sexual immorality and idolatry with Moabite women at Baal-peor, and 24,000 died in the plague. Phinehas (the very priest leading this delegation) was the one who stopped the plague by killing the Israelite man and Midianite woman (Num 25:7-8). His presence here is no accident -- he is the embodiment of zealous covenant enforcement.',
        20: 'The Achan precedent (Joshua 7): one man\'s sin with the devoted things brought defeat on the entire nation at Ai. Corporate responsibility is the principle -- one tribe\'s apostasy could bring judgment on all twelve. This is why the western tribes cannot simply ignore the eastern altar.',
        22: '\'The Mighty One, God, the LORD! The Mighty One, God, the LORD!\' -- El, Elohim, YHWH -- the triple divine name invoked twice. This is an extraordinary oath formula of the highest solemnity. The eastern tribes call upon the full majesty of God as witness to their innocence. They even invoke self-imprecation: \'do not save us this day\' if we are guilty. This is a covenant oath -- staking their lives on their truthfulness.',
        27: 'The altar is \'a witness\' (ed) -- not for sacrifice but for testimony. It exists to prove that the eastern tribes belong to YHWH\'s covenant community. Their concern was generational: future western Israelites might use the Jordan as a theological boundary, excluding the eastern tribes from YHWH worship. The altar is a permanent rebuttal to any such exclusion.',
        31: '\'Today we know that the LORD is in our midst.\' Phinehas\'s declaration is the resolution: YHWH\'s presence (and therefore His blessing) continues because no covenant breach has occurred. The phrase \'you have delivered the sons of Israel from the hand of the LORD\' is striking -- corporate punishment was averted because the accusation was false. God\'s judgment is real, but so is His mercy when His people act rightly.',
        34: 'The altar is named \'Witness\' (Ed). The Hebrew text may read simply: \'a witness between us that the LORD is God.\' The altar stands as a permanent testimony to covenant unity across geographic boundaries. CHRIST CONNECTION: The body of Christ transcends every geographic, ethnic, and cultural boundary (Eph 2:14-16). There is no \'Jordan\' that divides God\'s people in Christ.',
    },
    23: {
        1: '\'After many days\' -- an indefinite period has passed since the conquest. Joshua is now \'old, advanced in years\' (zaqen, ba bayamim). Farewell addresses by dying leaders are a recognized genre in both the Hebrew Bible and the ANE (cf. Jacob in Gen 49; Moses in Deut 31-33; David in 1 Chr 28-29; Paul in Acts 20:17-38).',
        3: '\'The LORD your God is the one who has been fighting for you.\' The attribution is total. Every military victory belongs to YHWH. Israel\'s strength was never in their armies or strategy but in the divine warrior who fought on their behalf. This is the consistent testimony of the entire conquest narrative.',
        6: '\'The Book of the Law of Moses\' -- the written Torah is the standard of covenant faithfulness. Joshua\'s charge presupposes a written, authoritative document that Israel is obligated to \'keep and do.\' The phrase \'not turn aside to the right or to the left\' echoes Deuteronomy 5:32 and 17:11, 20. Obedience means no deviation in any direction.',
        7: '\'Do not make mention of the name of their gods, nor swear by them, nor serve them, nor bow down to them.\' Four prohibitions escalating from speech to worship. Even speaking a pagan god\'s name in a reverent or oath context was forbidden (Exod 23:13). In the ANE, naming a deity invoked its power and acknowledged its jurisdiction.',
        10: '\'One man of you puts to flight a thousand.\' Echoes Deuteronomy 32:30 and Leviticus 26:8. The point is not Israelite valor but divine power -- YHWH is the one who fights, and His strength makes the numerical odds irrelevant.',
        13: 'Four metaphors for the danger of the remaining nations: (1) a snare (moqesh -- a bird trap), (2) a trap (pach -- a hunter\'s net), (3) a whip on your sides (shot -- a scourge), (4) thorns in your eyes (tseninim). The nations that Israel fails to drive out will become instruments of torment. This is fulfilled graphically throughout the book of Judges.',
        14: 'Joshua\'s deathbed confession: \'I am going today the way of all the earth.\' He faces death with clarity and uses his dying authority to testify: \'Not one word has failed of all the good words which the LORD your God spoke concerning you; all have come to pass for you.\' God\'s faithfulness is 100%. Every promise kept, every word fulfilled. This echoes 21:45 and is the theological anchor of the entire book. CRITICAL: Joshua uses this perfect track record of blessing to ground his warning -- the same God who kept every promise of good will also keep every warning of judgment (v. 15).',
        15: 'The terrifying corollary to v. 14: \'just as every good word... has come upon you, so the LORD will bring upon you every evil word.\' God\'s faithfulness is symmetrical. He does not keep promises of blessing while ignoring warnings of judgment. The same attribute -- absolute faithfulness to His word -- guarantees both. This is fulfilled in the exile (2 Kings 17:7-23; 25:1-21). The good land can be lost.',
        16: '\'When you transgress the covenant of the LORD your God.\' Not \'if\' but \'when\' -- Joshua\'s language carries prophetic weight. He knows this people. The book of Judges immediately demonstrates how right he was. Serving \'other gods\' (elohim acherim) is the covenant\'s cardinal violation, and it triggers \'the anger of the LORD\' (aph YHWH) -- His covenant wrath against unfaithfulness.',
    },
    24: {
        1: 'Joshua assembles all Israel at Shechem -- the most covenantally significant location in the land. Abraham first received the land promise here (Gen 12:6-7). Jacob buried his household\'s foreign gods here (Gen 35:2-4). Joshua renewed the covenant here after Ai (Josh 8:30-35). \'They presented themselves before God\' (lifnei ha\'elohim) indicates a formal cultic assembly, likely before the ark.',
        2: '\'Your fathers dwelt beyond the River from ancient times... and they served other gods.\' YHWH\'s historical prologue begins with a stunning admission: Israel\'s patriarchal family was pagan. Terah, Abraham\'s father, worshipped the gods of Mesopotamia. \'Beyond the River\' (ever hanahar) means east of the Euphrates -- Ur and Haran. The \'other gods\' (elohim acherim) are not denied or dismissed as nonexistent; they are real spiritual beings from whose jurisdiction YHWH extracted Abraham. Joshua 24:2 is one of the Bible\'s most honest verses about Israel\'s origins: chosen not because of ancestral piety but despite ancestral idolatry.',
        3: '\'I took your father Abraham from beyond the River.\' The verb laqach (took) implies sovereign divine action -- YHWH reached into Mesopotamian territory and extracted Abraham. God initiated the relationship. Abraham did not seek YHWH; YHWH called Abraham (Gen 12:1). This is pure grace.',
        7: '\'He set darkness between you and the Egyptians\' -- likely referring to the pillar of cloud/fire (Exod 14:19-20) that separated the Israelite camp from the Egyptian army at the Red Sea. \'Your eyes saw what I did in Egypt\' -- YHWH addresses the current generation as if they were present at the Exodus. Corporate memory collapses time: every generation of Israel participates in the founding events.',
        9: 'Balak and Balaam: Numbers 22-24. Balak hired Balaam to curse Israel, but YHWH turned every curse into a blessing. \'I was not willing to listen to Balaam\' -- God\'s sovereign control over even pagan prophets. Balaam could not curse what God had blessed (Num 23:20).',
        12: '\'I sent the hornet before you.\' The tsirah (hornet) appears in Exodus 23:28 and Deuteronomy 7:20 as a divine weapon. Whether literal insects, a metaphor for panic and terror, or a reference to Egyptian military campaigns that weakened Canaan before Israel\'s arrival, the point is the same: \'not by your sword and not by your bow.\' Israel\'s conquest was accomplished by divine power, not human military might.',
        13: '\'A land for which you did not labor, cities which you did not build, vineyards and olive groves which you did not plant.\' Everything Israel possesses is a gift. This is the theological foundation for the demand that follows: since everything comes from God, serve God alone. Grace precedes law. Gift precedes obligation. This is the structure of every biblical covenant -- and the structure of the gospel (Eph 2:8-10).',
        14: '\'Put away the gods which your fathers served beyond the River and in Egypt.\' The command to \'put away\' (hasiru) implies that some Israelites still possessed foreign gods -- household idols, Egyptian amulets, Canaanite figurines. Jacob issued the same command at this same location (Gen 35:2-4). Centuries later, the same idolatrous tendency persists. Ezekiel 20:7-8 confirms that Israel never fully abandoned Egyptian gods.',
        15: '\'Choose for yourselves today whom you will serve... but as for me and my house, we will serve the LORD.\' The most famous verse in Joshua. The choice is presented as genuine and urgent: \'today\' (hayyom). Joshua names three options: (1) the gods of Mesopotamia, (2) the gods of Canaan, (3) the LORD. He does not argue -- he declares his own decision and demands theirs. THEOLOGICAL SIGNIFICANCE: This verse demonstrates that covenant faithfulness is a conscious choice, not an inherited status. Each generation must choose. Each household must decide. CHRIST CONNECTION: Jesus presents the same binary -- \'No one can serve two masters\' (Matt 6:24). Joshua\'s either/or anticipates Christ\'s either/or. There is no neutral ground.',
        19: '\'You are not able to serve the LORD, for He is a holy God. He is a jealous God; He will not forgive your transgression or your sins.\' Joshua\'s shocking response to the people\'s pledge. This is NOT saying God never forgives -- the entire sacrificial system exists because He does. Joshua is saying: You cannot serve YHWH casually. You cannot serve Him while keeping your foreign gods. His holiness (qodesh) consumes everything impure. His jealousy (qin\'ah) tolerates no rivals. Presumptuous, half-hearted worship of the holy God leads to judgment, not blessing. Only through the coming Messiah\'s perfect sacrifice would full and final forgiveness be accomplished (Heb 9:12-14; 10:10-14). Joshua is driving the people to understand the weight of their commitment.',
        22: '\'You are witnesses against yourselves that you have chosen the LORD.\' Joshua makes the people self-witnesses -- they testify against themselves that they have voluntarily committed to YHWH. If they later apostatize, they cannot claim ignorance. Their own words condemn them. This is covenant ratification language -- binding, irrevocable, and witnessed.',
        25: 'Joshua makes a formal covenant (berit) and establishes \'a statute and an ordinance\' (choq umishpat). This follows the ANE suzerainty treaty pattern: (1) preamble (v. 2a), (2) historical prologue (vv. 2b-13), (3) stipulations (vv. 14-24), (4) document deposit (v. 26), (5) witnesses (vv. 26-27). The Shechem covenant is a formal renewal of the Sinai/Moab covenant for a new generation in a new land.',
        26: '\'Joshua wrote these words in the Book of the Law of God.\' He adds to the sacred written text -- the Torah is not a closed, inaccessible document but a living covenant record. The \'great stone\' under the \'oak\' (elah, or terebinth) at the sanctuary serves as a permanent witness marker. Standing stones as covenant witnesses are well attested throughout the ANE (cf. Gen 28:18; 31:44-52; Exod 24:4).',
        27: '\'This stone has heard all the words of the LORD which He spoke with us.\' The personification of the stone as a hearing witness echoes Deuteronomy 30:19 and 31:28, where Moses calls heaven and earth as witnesses. In the ANE, deities and cosmic elements were standard covenant witnesses. Here a stone assumes that function -- silent, enduring, immovable testimony to the covenant commitment.',
        29: 'Joshua dies at 110 years old -- the same age as Joseph (Gen 50:26). In Egyptian tradition, 110 was the ideal lifespan, the age of perfect blessing. Joshua receives the supreme title: \'the servant of the LORD\' (eved YHWH) -- the same title held by Moses (Josh 1:1). Joshua earned this title at death, not during life. He finished the race. He kept the faith.',
        31: '\'Israel served the LORD all the days of Joshua and all the days of the elders who survived Joshua.\' Faithfulness lasted exactly one generation -- the generation that had seen God\'s works. The generation that only heard about them abandoned the covenant (Judg 2:10-12). This is the perpetual danger: secondhand faith does not hold. Every generation must encounter God for itself.',
        32: 'Joseph\'s bones, carried out of Egypt at the Exodus (Exod 13:19), are finally buried at Shechem -- in the very plot of ground Jacob purchased (Gen 33:19). Joseph\'s dying wish (Gen 50:25) is fulfilled after more than 400 years. The bones traveled through the Red Sea, through 40 years of wilderness wandering, across the Jordan, through the conquest -- and now rest in the Promised Land. GOD KEEPS HIS PROMISES ACROSS GENERATIONS. No promise of God expires. No oath of God is forgotten. The burial of Joseph\'s bones is the quiet, definitive proof of God\'s faithfulness to His word.',
        33: 'Eleazar the son of Aaron dies -- the end of the priestly leader who served alongside Joshua throughout the conquest and allotment. He is buried \'in the hill of Phinehas his son\' in the hill country of Ephraim. The book ends with three burials: Joshua (the commander), Joseph (the patriarch), Eleazar (the priest). The conquest generation passes. The land is settled. The covenant has been renewed. What comes next -- the book of Judges -- will reveal whether the Shechem commitment holds. It does not.',
    },
}
